<BODY>
<H1>
<CENTER>GLSL Tutorial von Lighthouse3D</CENTER></H1><BR>Source: <A =
href=3D"http://www.lighthouse3d.com/opengl/glsl/">Lighthouse3D=20
GLSL Tutorial</A>. <BR><SMALL>I have concatenated all the seperate HTML =
pages of=20
the original tutorial for your reading convenience.<BR>I have also found =
that=20
the repetition of all code examples, once using OpenGL 2.0 syntax, and =
once=20
using ARB syntax, makes reading a little tedious; therefore, i have =
removed the=20
ARB versions of the examples, since they are outdated anyway. </SMALL>=20
<H2>Introduction </H2><BR>In this tutorial shader programming using GLSL =
will be=20
covered. Shaders are a hot topic and 3D games have shown that they can =
be put to=20
good use to get remarkable effects. This tutorial aims at providing an=20
introduction to the world of shaders.=20
<P>There is an introduction to the specification, but reading the <A =
href=3D"http://www.opengl.org/documentation/current_version/">OpenGL=20
2.0</A> and <A =
href=3D"http://www.opengl.org/documentation/glsl">GLSL</A> official=20
specs is always recommended if you get serious about this. It is assumed =
that=20
the reader is familiar with OpenGL programming, as this is required to=20
understand some parts of the tutorial.=20
<P>GLSL stands for GL Shading Language, often referred as =
<I>glslang</I>, and=20
was defined by the Architectural Review Board of OpenGL, the governing =
body of=20
OpenGL.=20
<P>I won't go into disputes, or comparisons, with Cg, Nvidia's proposal =
for a=20
shading language that is also compatible with OpenGL. The only reason I =
chose=20
GLSL and not Cg for this tutorial, is GLSL closeness to OpenGL.=20
<P>Before writing shaders, in any language, it is a good idea to =
understand the=20
basics of the graphics pipeline. This will provide a context to =
introduce=20
shaders, what types of shaders are available, and what shaders are =
supposed to=20
do. It will also show what shaders can't do, which is equally important. =

<P>After this introduction the OpenGL setup for GLSL is discussed. The =
necessary=20
steps to use a shader in an OpenGL application are discussed in some =
detail.=20
Finally it is shown how an OpenGL application can feed data to a shader =
making=20
it more flexible and powerful.=20
<P>Some basic concepts such as data types, variables, statements and =
function=20
definition are then introduced.=20
<P>The tutorial covers only the OpenGL 2.0 version (the ARB version has =
been=20
omitted and is deprecated). OpenGL 2.0 is color coded in <SPAN=20
class=3D"ogl">orange</SPAN>.=20
<P>Please bear in mind that this is work in progress and therefore bugs =
are=20
likely to be present in the text or demos. Let me know if you find any =
bug,=20
regardless of how insignificant, so that I can clean them up. Also =
suggestions=20
are more than welcome. I hope you enjoy the tutorial. =20
<P><A name=3D"pipeline"></A>=20
<H2>Pipeline Overview </H2><BR>The following figure is a (very) =
simplified=20
diagram of the pipeline stages and the data that travels amongst them. =
Although=20
extremely simplified it is enough to present some important concepts for =
shader=20
programming. In this subsection the fixed functionality of the pipeline =
is=20
presented. Note that this pipeline is an abstraction and does not =
necessarily=20
meet any particular implementation in all its steps.=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"500" height=3D"320" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/pipeline.gif"></CENTER>
<P><BR>
<P><B>Vertex Transformation</B>
<P>In here a vertex is a set of attributes such as its location in =
space, as=20
well as its color, normal, texture coordinates, amongst others. The =
inputs for=20
this stage are the individual vertices attributes. Some of the =
operations=20
performed by the fixed functionality at this stage are:=20
<UL>
  <LI>Vertex position transformation</LI>
  <LI>Lighting computations per vertex</LI>
  <LI>Generation and transformation of texture coordinates</LI></UL>
<P><B>Primitive Assembly and Rasterization</B>
<P>The inputs for this stage are the transformed vertices, as well as=20
connectivity information. This latter piece of data tells the pipeline =
how the=20
vertices connect to form a primitive. It is in here that primitives are=20
assembled.=20
<P>This stage is also responsible for clipping operations against the =
view=20
frustum, and back face culling.=20
<P>Rasterization determines the fragments, and pixel positions of the =
primitive.=20
A fragment in this context is a piece of data that will be used to =
update a=20
pixel in the frame buffer at a specific location. A fragment contains =
not only=20
color, but also normals and texture coordinates, amongst other possible=20
attributes, that are used to compute the new pixel's color.=20
<P> The output of this stage is twofold:=20
<UL>
  <LI>The position of the fragments in the frame buffer</LI>
  <LI>The interpolated values for each fragment of the attributes =
computed in=20
  the vertex transformation stage</LI></UL>The values computed at the =
vertex=20
transformation stage, combined with the vertex connectivity information =
allow=20
this stage to compute the appropriate attributes for the fragment. For =
instance,=20
each vertex has a transformed position. When considering the vertices =
that make=20
up a primitive, it is possible to compute the position of the fragments =
of the=20
primitive. Another example is the usage of color. If a triangle has its =
vertices=20
with different colors, then the color of the fragments inside the =
triangle are=20
obtained by interpolation of the triangle's vertices color weighted by =
the=20
relative distances of the vertices to the fragment.=20
<P><B>Fragment Texturing and Coloring</B>
<P>Interpolated fragment information is the input of this stage. A color =
has=20
already been computed in the previous stage through interpolation, and =
in here=20
it can be combined with a texel (texture element) for example. Texture=20
coordinates have also been interpolated in the previous stage. Fog is =
also=20
applied at this stage. The common end result of this stage per fragment =
is a=20
color value and a depth for the fragment. =20
<P><B>Raster Operations</B>
<P>The inputs of this stage are:=20
<UL>
  <LI>The pixels location</LI>
  <LI>The fragments depth and color values</LI></UL>The last stage of =
the pipeline=20
performs a series of tests on the fragment, namely:=20
<UL>
  <LI>Scissor test</LI>
  <LI>Alpha test</LI>
  <LI>Stencil test</LI>
  <LI>Depth test</LI></UL>If successful the fragment information is then =
used to=20
update the pixel's value according to the current blend mode. Notice =
that=20
blending occurs only at this stage because the Fragment Texturing and =
Coloring=20
stage has no access to the frame buffer. The frame buffer is only =
accessible at=20
this stage.=20
<P><B>Visual Summary of the Fixed Functionality</B>
<P>The following figure presents a visual description of the stages =
presented=20
above:=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"542" height=3D"297" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/visualpipeline.gif"></CENTER>
<P><BR>
<P><B>Replacing Fixed Functionality</B>
<P>Recent graphic cards give the programmer the ability to define the=20
functionality of two of the above described stages:=20
<UL>
  <LI>Vertex shaders may be written for the Vertex Transformation =
stage.</LI>
  <LI>Fragment shaders replace the Fragment Texturing and Coloring =
stage's fixed=20
  functionality.</LI></UL>In the next subsections these programmable =
stages,=20
hereafter the vertex processor and the fragment processor, are =
described. <A=20
name=3D"vertexp"></A>=20
<H2>    Vertex Processor </H2><BR>The vertex processor is responsible =
for=20
running the vertex shaders. The input for a vertex shader is the vertex =
data,=20
namely its position, color, normals, etc, depending on what the OpenGL=20
application sends. =20
<P>The following OpenGL code would send to the vertex processor a color =
and a=20
vertex position for each vertex.=20
<HR>

<PRE>	glBegin(...);=0A=
=0A=
		glColor3f(0.2,0.4,0.6);=0A=
		glVertex3f(-1.0,1.0,2.0);=0A=
=0A=
		glColor3f(0.2,0.4,0.8);=0A=
		glVertex3f(1.0,-1.0,2.0);=0A=
=0A=
	glEnd();=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>In a vertex shader you can write code for tasks such as:=20
<UL>
  <LI>Vertex position transformation using the modelview and projection=20
  matrices</LI>
  <LI>Normal transformation, and if required its normalization</LI>
  <LI>Texture coordinate generation and transformation</LI>
  <LI>Lighting per vertex or computing values for lighting per =
pixel</LI>
  <LI>Color computation</LI></UL>There is no requirement to perform all =
the=20
operations above, your application may not use lighting for instance. =
However,=20
once you write a vertex shader you are replacing the full functionality =
of the=20
vertex processor, hence you can't perform normal transformation and =
expect the=20
fixed functionality to perform texture coordinate generation. When a =
vertex=20
shader is used it becomes responsible for replacing all the needed =
functionality=20
of this stage of the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.php#pipeline">pipeline</A>.=20
<P>As can be seen in the previous <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.php#pipeline">subsection</A>=20
the vertex processor has no information regarding connectivity, hence =
operations=20
that require topological knowledge can't be performed in here. For =
instance it=20
is not possible for a vertex shader to perform back face culling, since =
it=20
operates on vertices and not on faces. The vertex processor processes =
vertices=20
individually and has no clue of the remaining vertices.=20
<P>The vertex shader is responsible for at least writing a variable:=20
<I>gl_Position</I>, usually transforming the vertex with the modelview =
and=20
projection matrices. =20
<P>A vertex processor has access to OpenGL state, so it can perform =
operations=20
that involve lighting for instance, and use materials. It can also =
access=20
textures (only available in the newest hardware). There is no access to =
the=20
frame buffer.=20
<P>
<H2>Fragment Processor </H2><BR>The fragment processor is where the =
fragment=20
shaders run. This unit is responsible for operations like:=20
<UL>
  <LI>Computing colors, and texture coordinates per pixel</LI>
  <LI>Texture application</LI>
  <LI>Fog computation</LI>
  <LI>Computing normals if you want lighting per pixel</LI></UL>The =
inputs for=20
this unit are the interpolated values computed in the previous stage of =
the=20
pipeline such as vertex positions, colors, normals, etc...=20
<P>In the vertex shader these values are computed for each vertex. Now =
we're=20
dealing with the fragments inside the primitives, hence the need for the =

interpolated values.=20
<P>As in the vertex processor, when you write a fragment shader it =
replaces all=20
the fixed functionality. Therefore it is not possible to have a fragment =
shader=20
texturing the fragment and leave the fog for the fixed functionality. =
The=20
programmer must code all effects that the application requires.=20
<P>The fragment processor operates on single fragments, i.e. it has no =
clue=20
about the neighboring fragments. The shader has access to OpenGL state, =
similar=20
to the vertex shaders, and therefore it can access for instance the fog =
color=20
specified in an OpenGL application.=20
<P>One important point is that a fragment shader can't change the pixel=20
coordinate, as computed previously in the pipeline. Recall that in the =
vertex=20
processor the modelview and projection matrices can be used to transform =
the=20
vertex. The viewport comes into play after that but before the fragment=20
processor. The fragment shader has access to the pixels location on =
screen but=20
it can't change it.=20
<P>A fragment shader has two output options:=20
<UL>
  <LI>to discard the fragment, hence outputting nothing</LI>
  <LI>to compute either <I>gl_FragColor</I> (the final color of the =
fragment),=20
  or <I>gl_FragData</I> when rendering to multiple =
targets.</LI></UL>Depth can=20
also be written although it is not required since the previous stage =
already has=20
computed it.=20
<P>Notice that the fragment shader has no access to the frame buffer. =
This=20
implies that operations such as blending occur only after the fragment =
shader=20
has run.=20
<P>
<H2>OpenGL Setup for GLSL - Overview </H2><BR>This section, OpenGL Setup =
for=20
GLSL, assumes you've got a pair of shaders, a vertex shader and a =
fragment=20
shader, and you want to use them in an OpenGL application. If you're not =
ready=20
yet to write your own shaders there are plenty of places to get shaders =
from the=20
internet. Try the <A href=3D"http://www.3dshaders.com/">site</A> from =
the Orange=20
Book. The tools for shader development, namely <A =
href=3D"http://www.typhoonlabs.com/">Shader=20
Designer</A> or <A href=3D"http://developer.ati.com/">Render Monkey</A>, =
all have=20
a lot of shader examples.=20
<P>As far as OpenGL goes, setting your application is similar to the =
workflow of=20
writing a C program. Each shader is like a C module, and it must be=20
<B>compiled</B> separately, as in C. The set of compiled shaders, is =
then=20
<B>linked</B> into a program, exactly as in C.=20
<P>To check for OpenGL 2.0 availability you could try something like =
this=20
<HR>

<PRE class=3D"ogl">	#include &lt;GL/glew.h&gt;=0A=
	#include &lt;GL/glut.h&gt;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main(int argc, char **argv) {=0A=
	=0A=
		glutInit(&amp;argc, argv);=0A=
		=0A=
		...=0A=
		=0A=
		glewInit();=0A=
		if (glewIsSupported("GL_VERSION_2_0"))=0A=
			printf("Ready for OpenGL 2.0\n");=0A=
		else {=0A=
			printf("OpenGL 2.0 not supported\n");=0A=
			exit(1);=0A=
		}=0A=
	=0A=
		setShaders();=0A=
	=0A=
		glutMainLoop();=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The figure below shows the necessary steps (in OpenGL 2.0 syntax) to =
create=20
the shaders, the functions used will be detailed in latter sections. =20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"461" height=3D"375" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/ogloverview.gif"></CENTER>
<P><BR>
<P>In the next subsections the steps to create a program are detailed. =
<A name=3D"oglshader"></A>=20
<A name=3D"oglprogram"></A>=20
<H2>OpenGL Setup for GLSL - Creating a Shader </H2><BR>The following =
figure=20
shows the necessary steps to create a shader.=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"268" height=3D"184" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/oglshader.gif"></CENTER>
<P><BR>The first step is creating an object which will act as a shader=20
container. The function available for this purpose returns a handle for =
the=20
container.=20
<P>The OpenGL 2.0 syntax for this function is as follows:=20
<P class=3D"ogl">
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">GLuint glCreateShader(GLenum shaderType);=20
<P>Parameter:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>shaderType - GL_VERTEX_SHADER or GL_FRAGMENT_SHADER.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>You can create as many shaders as you want to add to a program, but =
remember=20
that there can only be a <I>main</I> function for the set of vertex =
shaders and=20
one <I>main</I> function for the set of fragment shaders in each single =
program.=20
<P>The following step is to add some source code. The source code for a =
shader=20
is a string array, although you can use a pointer to a single string.=20
<P>The syntax of the function to set the source code, in OpenGL 2.0 =
syntax, for=20
a shader is:=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glShaderSource(GLuint shader, int numOfStrings, =
const char=20
**strings, int *lenOfStrings);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>shader - the handler to the shader.</DD>
  <DD>numOfStrings - the number of strings in the array.</DD>
  <DD>strings - the array of strings.</DD>
  <DD>lenOfStrings - an array with the length of each string, or NULL, =
meaning=20
  that the strings are NULL terminated.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>Finally, the shader must be compiled. The function to achieve this =
using=20
OpenGL 2.0 is:=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glCompileShader(GLuint shader);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>shader - the handler to the shader.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>
<H2>OpenGL Setup for GLSL - Creating a Program </H2><BR>The following =
figure=20
shows the necessary steps to get a shader program ready and going.=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"146" height=3D"290" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/oglprogram.gif"></CENTER>
<P><BR>The first step is creating an object which will act as a program=20
container. The function available for this purpose returns a handle for =
the=20
container.=20
<P>The syntax for this function, in OpenGL 2.0 syntax is as follows:=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">GLuint glCreateProgram(void);=20
<P>
<HR>

<P>You can create as many programs as you want. Once rendering, you can =
switch=20
from program to program, and even go back to fixed functionality during =
a single=20
frame. For instance you may want to draw a teapot with refraction and =
reflection=20
shaders, while having a cube map displayed for background using OpenGL's =
fixed=20
functionality.=20
<P>The next step involves attaching the shaders created in the previous =
<A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#oglshader">subsection</A>=20
to the program you've just created. The shaders do not need to be =
compiled at=20
this time; they don't even have to have source code. All that is =
required to=20
attach a shader to a program is the shader container.=20
<P>To attach a shader to a program use the OpenGL 2.0 function: =20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glAttachShader(GLuint program, GLuint shader);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>program - the handler to the program.</DD>
  <DD>shader - the handler to the shader you want to attach.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>If you have a pair vertex/fragment of shaders you'll need to attach =
both to=20
the program. You can have many shaders of the same type (vertex or =
fragment)=20
attached to the same program, just like a C program can have many =
modules. For=20
each type of shader there can only be one shader with a <I>main</I> =
function,=20
also as in C.=20
<P>You can attach a shader to multiple programs, for instance if you =
plan to use=20
the same vertex shader in several programs.=20
<P>The final step is to link the program. In order to carry out this =
step the=20
shaders must be compiled as described in the previous subsection.=20
<P>The syntax for the link function, in OpenGL 2.0, is as follows:=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glLinkProgram(GLuint program);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>program - the handler to the program.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>After the link operation the shader's source can be modified, and the =
shaders=20
recompiled without affecting the program.=20
<P>As shown in the figure above, after linking the program, there is a =
function=20
to actually load and use the program (OpenGL 2.0) <I=20
class=3D"ogl">glUseProgram</I>. Each program is assigned an handler, and =
you can=20
have as many programs linked and ready to use as you want (and your =
hardware=20
allows).=20
<P>The syntax for this function is as follows (OpenGL 2.0 notation):=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glUseProgram(GLuint prog);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>prog - the handler to the program you want to use, or zero to =
return to=20
  fixed functionality</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>If a program is in use, and it is linked again, it will automatically =
be=20
placed in use again, so in this case you don't need to call this =
function again.=20
I the parameter is zero then the fixed functionality is activated.=20
<H2>OpenGL Setup for GLSL - Example </H2><BR>The following source code =
contains=20
all the steps described previously. The variables <I>p,f,v</I> are =
declared=20
globally as (OpenGL 2.0 syntax) <I class=3D"ogl">GLuint</I>. =20
<P>OpenGL 2.0 syntax:=20
<HR>

<PRE class=3D"ogl">	void setShaders() {=0A=
	=0A=
		char *vs,*fs;=0A=
	=0A=
		v =3D glCreateShader(GL_VERTEX_SHADER);=0A=
		f =3D glCreateShader(GL_FRAGMENT_SHADER);	=0A=
	=0A=
		vs =3D textFileRead("toon.vert");=0A=
		fs =3D textFileRead("toon.frag");=0A=
	=0A=
		const char * vv =3D vs;=0A=
		const char * ff =3D fs;=0A=
	=0A=
		glShaderSource(v, 1, &amp;vv,NULL);=0A=
		glShaderSource(f, 1, &amp;ff,NULL);=0A=
	=0A=
		free(vs);free(fs);=0A=
	=0A=
		glCompileShader(v);=0A=
		glCompileShader(f);=0A=
	=0A=
		p =3D glCreateProgram();=0A=
		=0A=
		glAttachShader(p,v);=0A=
		glAttachShader(p,f);=0A=
	=0A=
		glLinkProgram(p);=0A=
		glUseProgram(p);=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>A complete GLUT example is available: <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/glutglsl_2.0.zip">OpenGL=20
2.0 syntax</A>, containing two simple shaders, and the text file reading =

functions.=20
<P>
<H2>OpenGL Setup for GLSL - Troubleshooting: The InfoLog =
</H2><BR>Debugging a=20
shader is hard. There is no <I>printf</I> yet and probably never will =
be,=20
although developer tools with debugging capability are to be expected in =
the=20
future. It is true that you can use some tricks now but these are not =
trivial by=20
any means. All is not lost and some functions are provided to check if =
your code=20
compiled and linked successfully.=20
<P>The status of the compile steps can be queried in OpenGL 2.0 with the =

following function:=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glGetShaderiv(GLuint object, GLenum type, int =
*param);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>object - the handler to the object. Either a shader or a =
program</DD>
  <DD>type - GL_COMPILE_STATUS.</DD>
  <DD>param - the return value, GL_TRUE if OK, GL_FALSE =
otherwise.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>The status of the link step can be queried in OpenGL 2.0 with the =
following=20
function:=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glGetProgramiv(GLuint object, GLenum type, int =
*param);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>object - the handler to the object. Either a shader or a =
program</DD>
  <DD>type - GL_LINK_STATUS.</DD>
  <DD>param - the return value, GL_TRUE if OK, GL_FALSE =
otherwise.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>There are more options regarding the second parameter, <I>type</I>, =
however=20
these won't be explored in here. Check out the 3Dlabs <A =
href=3D"http://developer.3dlabs.com/openGL2/index.htm">site</A>=20
for the complete specification.=20
<P>When errors are reported it is possible to get further information =
with the=20
InfoLog. This log stores information about the last operation performed, =
such as=20
warnings and errors in the compilation, problems during the link step. =
The log=20
can even tell you if your shaders will run in software, meaning your =
hardware=20
does not support some feature you're using, or hardware, the ideal =
situation.=20
Unfortunately there is no specification for the InfoLog messages, so =
different=20
drivers/hardware may produce different logs.=20
<P>In order to get the InfoLog  for a particular shader or program in =
OpenGL 2.0=20
use the following functions:=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glGetShaderInfoLog(GLuint object, int maxLen, int =
*len, char=20
*log); <BR class=3D"ogl">void glGetProgramInfoLog(GLuint object, int =
maxLen, int=20
*len, char *log);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>object - the handler to the object. Either a shader or a =
program</DD>
  <DD>maxLen - The maximum number of chars to retrieve from the =
InfoLog.</DD>
  <DD>len - returns the actual length of the retrieved InfoLog.</DD>
  <DD>log - The log itself.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>The GLSL specification could have been nicer in here. You must know =
the=20
length of the InfoLog to retrieve it. To find this precious bit of =
information=20
use the following functions (in OpenGL notation):=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glGetShaderiv(GLuint object, GLenum type, int =
*param); <BR=20
class=3D"ogl">void glGetProgramiv(GLuint object, GLenum type, int =
*param);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>object - the handler to the object. Either a shader or a =
program</DD>
  <DD>type - GL_INFO_LOG_LENGTH.</DD>
  <DD>param - the return value, the length of the InfoLog.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>The following functions can be used to print the contents of the =
infoLog in=20
OpenGL 2.0:=20
<HR>

<PRE class=3D"ogl">	void printShaderInfoLog(GLuint obj)=0A=
	{=0A=
	    int infologLength =3D 0;=0A=
	    int charsWritten  =3D 0;=0A=
	    char *infoLog;=0A=
=0A=
		glGetShaderiv(obj, GL_INFO_LOG_LENGTH,&amp;infologLength);=0A=
=0A=
	    if (infologLength &gt; 0)=0A=
	    {=0A=
	        infoLog =3D (char *)malloc(infologLength);=0A=
	        glGetShaderInfoLog(obj, infologLength, &amp;charsWritten, =
infoLog);=0A=
			printf("%s\n",infoLog);=0A=
	        free(infoLog);=0A=
	    }=0A=
	}=0A=
=0A=
	void printProgramInfoLog(GLuint obj)=0A=
	{=0A=
	    int infologLength =3D 0;=0A=
	    int charsWritten  =3D 0;=0A=
	    char *infoLog;=0A=
=0A=
		glGetProgramiv(obj, GL_INFO_LOG_LENGTH,&amp;infologLength);=0A=
=0A=
	    if (infologLength &gt; 0)=0A=
	    {=0A=
	        infoLog =3D (char *)malloc(infologLength);=0A=
	        glGetProgramInfoLog(obj, infologLength, &amp;charsWritten, =
infoLog);=0A=
			printf("%s\n",infoLog);=0A=
	        free(infoLog);=0A=
	    }=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>
<H2>OpenGL Setup for GLSL - Cleaning Up </H2><BR>In a previous <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#oglprogram">subsection</A>=20
a function to attach a shader to a program was presented. A function to =
detach a=20
shader from a program is also available.=20
<P>The OpenGL 2.0 syntax is as follows:=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glDetachShader(GLuint program, GLuint shader);=20
<P>Parameter:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>program - The program to detach from.</DD>
  <DD>shader - The shader to detach.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>Only shaders that are not attached can be deleted so this operation =
is not=20
irrelevant. To delete a shader, or a program, in OpenGL 2.0, use the =
following=20
functions:=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glDeleteShader(GLuint id); <BR class=3D"ogl">void=20
glDeleteProgram(GLuint id);=20
<P>Parameter:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>id - The handler of the shader or program to delete.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>In the case of a shader that is still attached to some (one or more)=20
programs, the shader is not actually deleted, but only marked for =
deletion. The=20
delete operation will only be concluded when the shader is no longer =
attached to=20
any program, i.e. it has been detached from all programs it was attached =
to.=20
<P>
<H2>
<CENTER>OpenGL Setup for GLSL - Communication OpenGL -&gt; Shaders=20
</CENTER></H2><BR>An application in OpenGL has several ways of =
communicating=20
with the shaders. Note that this is a one way communication though, =
since the=20
only output from a shader is to render to some targets, usually the =
color and=20
depth buffers.=20
<P> The shader has access to part of the OpenGL state, therefore when an =

application alters this subset of the OpenGL state it is effectively=20
communicating with the shader. So for instance if an application wants =
to pass a=20
light color to the shader it can simply alter the OpenGL state as it is =
normally=20
done with the fixed functionality.=20
<P>However, using the OpenGL state is not always the most intuitive way =
of=20
setting values for the shaders to act upon. For instance consider a =
shader that=20
requires a variable to tell the elapsed time to perform some animation. =
There is=20
no suitable named variable in the OpenGL state for this purpose. True, =
you can=20
use an unused lights specular cutoff angle for this but it is highly=20
counterintuitive.=20
<P>Fortunately, GLSL allows the definition of user defined variables for =
an=20
OpenGL application to communicate with a shader. Thanks to this simple =
feature=20
you can have a variable for time keeping appropriately called=20
<I>timeElapsed</I>, or some other suitable name.=20
<P>In this context, GLSL has two types of variable qualifiers (more =
qualifiers=20
are available to use inside a shader as detailed in <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#data">Data=20
Types and Variables subsection</A>): =20
<UL>
  <LI>Uniform</LI>
  <LI>Attribute</LI></UL>Variables defined in shaders using these =
qualifiers are=20
read-only as far as the shader is concerned. In the following =
subsections the=20
details of how, and when to use these types of variables are detailed.=20
<P>There is yet another way of sending values to shaders: using =
textures. A=20
texture doesn't have to represent an image; it can be interpreted as an =
array of=20
data. In fact, using shaders you're the one who decides how to interpret =
your=20
textures data, even when it is an image. The usage of textures is not =
explored=20
in this section since it is out of scope.=20
<P><A name=3D"ogluniform"></A>=20
<H2>OpenGL Setup for GLSL - Uniform Variables </H2><BR>A uniform =
variable can=20
have its value changed by primitive only, i.e., its value can't be =
changed=20
between a <I>glBegin</I> / <I>glEnd</I> pair. This implies that it can't =
be used=20
for vertices attributes. Look for the subsection on <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#oglattribute">attribute=20
variables</A> if that is what you're looking for. Uniform variables are =
suitable=20
for values that remain constant along a primitive, frame, or even the =
whole=20
scene. Uniform variables can be read (but not written) in both vertex =
and=20
fragment shaders. =20
<P>The first thing you have to do is to get the memory location of the =
variable.=20
Note that this information is only available after you link the program. =
Note:=20
with some drivers you may be required to be using the program, i.e. =
you'll have=20
to call (openGL 2.0) <SPAN class=3D"ogl"><I>glUSeProgram</I></SPAN> =
before=20
attempting to get the location (it happens with my laptop ATI graphics =
card).=20
<P>The function to retrieve the location of an uniform variable given =
its name,=20
as defined in the shader, is (OpenGL 2.0 syntax):=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">GLint glGetUniformLocation(GLuint program, const char =
*name);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>program - the handler to the program</DD>
  <DD>name - the name of the variable.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>The return value is the location of the variable, which can then be =
used to=20
assign values to it. A family of functions is provided for setting =
uniform=20
variables, its usage being dependent on the data type of the variable. A =
set of=20
functions is defined for setting float values as (OpenGL 2.0 notation):=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glUniform1f(GLint location, GLfloat v0);<BR>void=20
glUniform2f(GLint location, GLfloat v0, GLfloat v1);<BR>void =
glUniform3f(GLint=20
location, GLfloat v0, GLfloat v1, GLfloat v2);<BR>void glUniform4f(GLint =

location, GLfloat v0, GLfloat v1, GLfloat v2, GLfloat v3);=20
<P>or=20
<P>
<P class=3D"ogl">GLint glUniform{1,2,3,4}fv(GLint location, GLsizei =
count, GLfloat=20
*v);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>location - the previously queried location.</DD>
  <DD>v0,v1,v2,v3 - float values.</DD>
  <DD>count - the number of elements in the array</DD>
  <DD>v - an array of floats.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>A similar set of function is available for data type <I>integer</I>, =
where=20
"f" is replaced by "i". There are no functions specifically for bools, =
or=20
boolean vectors. Just use the functions available for <I>float</I> or=20
<I>integer</I> and set zero for false, and anything else for true. In =
case you=20
have an array of uniform variables the vector version should be used. =20
<P>For <I>sampler</I> variables, use the functions (OpenGL 2.0 notation) =
<I=20
class=3D"ogl">glUniform1i</I>, or <I class=3D"ogl">glUniform1iv</I> if =
setting an=20
array of samplers.=20
<P>Matrices are also an available data type in GLSL, and a set of =
functions is=20
also provided for this data type:=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">GLint glUniformMatrix{2,3,4}fv(GLint location, GLsizei =
count,=20
GLboolean transpose, GLfloat *v);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>location - the previously queried location.</DD>
  <DD>count - the number of matrices. 1 if a single matrix is being set, =
or=20
  <I>n</I> for an array of <I>n</I> matrices.</DD>
  <DD>transpose - wheter to transpose the matrix values. A value of 1 =
indicates=20
  that the matrix values are specified in row major order, zero is =
column major=20
  order</DD>
  <DD>v - an array of floats.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>An important note to close this subsection, and before some source =
code is=20
presented: the values that are set with these functions will keep their =
values=20
until the program is linked again. Once a new link process is performed =
all=20
values will be reset to zero.=20
<P>And now to some source code. Assume that a shader with the following=20
variables is being used:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	uniform float specIntensity;=0A=
	uniform vec4 specColor;=0A=
	uniform float t[2];=0A=
	uniform vec4 colors[3];=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>In an OpenGL 2.0 application, the code for setting the variables =
could be:=20
<HR>

<PRE class=3D"ogl">	GLint loc1,loc2,loc3,loc4;=0A=
	float specIntensity =3D 0.98;=0A=
	float sc[4] =3D {0.8,0.8,0.8,1.0};=0A=
	float threshold[2] =3D {0.5,0.25};=0A=
	float colors[12] =3D {0.4,0.4,0.8,1.0,=0A=
				  0.2,0.2,0.4,1.0,=0A=
				  0.1,0.1,0.1,1.0};=0A=
=0A=
	loc1 =3D glGetUniformLocation(p,"specIntensity");=0A=
	glUniform1f(loc1,specIntensity);=0A=
=0A=
	loc2 =3D glGetUniformLocation(p,"specColor");=0A=
	glUniform4fv(loc2,1,sc);=0A=
=0A=
	loc3 =3D glGetUniformLocation(p,"t");=0A=
	glUniform1fv(loc3,2,threshold);=0A=
=0A=
	loc4 =3D glGetUniformLocation(p,"colors");=0A=
	glUniform4fv(loc4,3,colors);=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>A working example, with source code, is available: <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/glutglsl2_2.0.zip">OpenGL=20
2.0 syntax</A>.=20
<P>Notice the difference between setting an array of values, as it is =
the case=20
of <I>t</I> or <I>colors</I>, and setting a vector with 4 values, as the =

<I>specColor</I>. The <I>count</I> parameter (middle parameter of <I=20
class=3D"ogl">glGetUniform{1,2,3,4}fv</I>) specifies the number of array =
elements=20
as declared in the shader, not as declared in the OpenGL application. So =

although <I>specColor</I> contains 4 values, the <I>count</I> of the =
function <I=20
class=3D"ogl">glUniform4fv</I> parameter is set to 1, because it is only =
one=20
vector. An alternative for setting the <I>specColor</I> variable could =
be:=20
<HR>

<PRE class=3D"ogl">	loc2 =3D glGetUniformLocation(p,"specColor");=0A=
	glUniform4f(loc2,sc[0],sc[1],sc[2],sc[3]);=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>
<P>Yet another possibility provided by GLSL is to get the location of a =
variable=20
inside an array. For instance, it is possible to get the location of =
t[1]. The=20
following snippet of code shows this approach to set the <I>t</I> array=20
elements.=20
<HR>

<PRE class=3D"ogl">	loct0 =3D glGetUniformLocation(p,"t[0]");=0A=
	glUniform1f(loct0,threshold[0]);=0A=
=0A=
	loct1 =3D glGetUniformLocation(p,"t[1]");=0A=
	glUniform1f(loct1,threshold[1]);=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>Notice how the variable is specified in <I=20
class=3D"ogl">glGetUniformLocation</I> using the square brackets.=20
<P><A name=3D"oglattribute"></A>=20
<H2>OpenGL Setup for GLSL - Attribute Variables </H2><BR>As mentioned in =

subsection <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogluniform">Uniform</A>,=20
uniform variables can only be set by primitive, i.e., they can't be set =
inside a=20
<I>glBegin-glEnd</I>.=20
<P>If it is required to set variables per vertex then attribute =
variables must=20
be used. In fact attribute variables can be updated at any time. =
Attribute=20
variables can only be read (not written) in a vertex shader. This is =
because=20
they contain  vertex data, hence not applicable directly in a fragment =
shader=20
(see the section on <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#varying">varying</A>=20
variables). As for <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogluniform">uniform</A>=20
variables, first it is necessary to get the location in memory of the =
variable.=20
Note that the program must be linked previously and some drivers may =
require=20
that the program is in use.=20
<P>In OpenGL 2.0 use the following function:=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">GLint glGetAttribLocation(GLuint program,char *name);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>program - the handle to the program.</DD>
  <DD>name - the name of the variable</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>The variable's location in memory is obtained as the return value of =
the=20
above function. The next step is to specify a value for it, potentially =
per=20
vertex. As in the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogluniform">uniform</A>=20
variables, there is a function for each data type.=20
<P>OpenGL 2.0 syntax:=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glVertexAttrib1f(GLint location, GLfloat =
v0);<BR>void=20
glVertexAttrib2f(GLint location, GLfloat v0, GLfloat v1);<BR>void=20
glVertexAttrib3f(GLint location, GLfloat v0, GLfloat v1,GLfloat =
v2);<BR>void=20
glVertexAttrib4f(GLint location, GLfloat v0, GLfloat v1,,GLfloat v2, =
GLfloat=20
v3);=20
<P>or=20
<P>
<P class=3D"ogl">GLint glVertexAttrib{1,2,3,4}fv(GLint location, GLfloat =
*v);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>location - the previously queried location.</DD>
  <DD>v0,v1,v2,v3 - float values.</DD>
  <DD>v - an array of floats.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>A similar set of functions is provided for <I>integers</I> and some =
other=20
data types. Note that the vector version is not available for arrays as =
is the=20
case of <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogluniform">uniform</A>=20
variables. The vector version is just an option to submit the values of =
a single=20
attribute variable. This is similar to what happens in OpenGL with=20
<I>glColor3f</I> and <I>glColor3fv</I>.=20
<P>A small example is now provided. It is assumed that the vertex shader =
declare=20
a float attribute named <I>height</I>. The setup phase, to be performed =
after=20
program link is:=20
<HR>

<PRE class=3D"ogl">	loc =3D glGetAttribLocation(p,"height");=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>In the rendering function the code could be something like:=20
<HR>

<PRE class=3D"ogl">	glBegin(GL_TRIANGLE_STRIP);=0A=
=0A=
		glVertexAttrib1f(loc,2.0);=0A=
		glVertex2f(-1,1);=0A=
=0A=
		glVertexAttrib1f(loc,2.0);=0A=
		glVertex2f(1,1);=0A=
=0A=
		glVertexAttrib1f(loc,-2.0);=0A=
		glVertex2f(-1,-1);=0A=
=0A=
		glVertexAttrib1f(loc,-2.0);=0A=
		glVertex2f(1,-1);=0A=
=0A=
	glEnd();=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The source code for a small working example is available: <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/glutglsl3_2.0.zip">OpenGL=20
2.0 syntax</A>.=20
<P>Vertex Arrays can also be used together with attribute variables. The =
first=20
thing to be done is to enable the arrays. To do this for an attribute =
array use=20
the following function (OpenGL 2.0 syntax):=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glEnableVertexAttribArray(GLint loc);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>loc - the location of the variable.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>Next the pointer to the array with the data is provided using the =
following=20
functions.=20
<P>OpenGL 2.0 syntax:=20
<HR>

<P class=3D"ogl">void glVertexAttribPointer(GLint loc, GLint size, =
GLenum type,=20
GLboolean normalized, GLsizei stride, const void *pointer);=20
<P>Parameters:=20
<DL class=3D"ogl">
  <DD>loc - the location of the variable.</DD>
  <DD>size - the number of components per element, for instance: 1 for =
float; 2=20
  for vec2; 3 for vec3, and so on.</DD>
  <DD>type - The data type associated: GL_FLOAT is an example.</DD>
  <DD>normalized - if set to 1 then the array values will be normalized, =

  converted to a range from -1 to 1 for signed data, or 0 to 1 for =
unsigned=20
  data.</DD>
  <DD>stride - the spacing between elements. Exactly the same as in =
OpenGL.</DD>
  <DD>pointer - pointer to the array containing the data.</DD></DL>
<HR>

<P>And now to some source code. First the initialization step. Two =
arrays are=20
considered, the vertex and attribute arrays. It is assumed that the =
variable=20
<I>heights</I> is declared with appropriate scope, i.e. accessible both =
in here=20
as well as when rendering.=20
<HR>

<PRE class=3D"ogl">=0A=
	float vertices[8] =3D {-1,1, 1,1, -1,-1, 1,-1};=0A=
	float heights[4] =3D {2,2,-2,-2};=0A=
	=0A=
	...=0A=
	=0A=
	loc =3D glGetAttribLocation(p,"height");=0A=
=0A=
	glEnableClientState(GL_VERTEX_ARRAY);=0A=
	glEnableVertexAttribArrayARB(loc);=0A=
=0A=
	glVertexPointer(2,GL_FLOAT,0,vertices);=0A=
	glVertexAttribPointer(loc,1,GL_FLOAT,0,0,heights);=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>Rendering is exactly the same as before (OpenGL without shaders), =
just call=20
<I>glDrawArrays</I> for example. A small demo source code is available: =
<A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/glutglsl4_2.0.zip">OpenGL=20
2.0 syntax</A>.=20
<P><A name=3D"data" a=3D"" <=3D""></A>
<H2><A name=3D"data" a=3D"" <=3D"">Data Types and Variables </A></H2><A =
name=3D"data" a=3D""=20
<=3D""><BR>The following simple data types are available in GLSL:=20
<UL>
  <LI>float</LI>
  <LI>bool</LI>
  <LI>int</LI></UL>Float and int behave just like in C, whereas the bool =
type can=20
take on the values of true or false.=20
<P>Vectors with 2,3 or 4 components are also available for each of the =
simple=20
data types mentioned above. These are declared as:=20
<UL>
  <LI>vec{2,3,4} a vector of 2,3,or 4 floats</LI>
  <LI>bvec{2,3,4} bool vector</LI>
  <LI>ivec{2,3,4} vector of integers</LI></UL>Square matrices 2x2, 3x3 =
and 4x4 are=20
provided since they are heavily used in graphics. The respective data =
types are:=20
<UL>
  <LI>mat2</LI>
  <LI>mat3</LI>
  <LI>mat4</LI></UL>A set of special types are available for texture =
access. These=20
are called samplers and are required to access texture values, also =
known as=20
texels. The data types for texture sampling are:=20
<UL>
  <LI>sampler1D - for 1D textures</LI>
  <LI>sampler2D - for 2D textures</LI>
  <LI>sampler3D - for 3D textures</LI>
  <LI>samplerCube - for cube map textures</LI>
  <LI>sampler1DShadow - for shadow maps</LI>
  <LI>sampler2DShadow - for shadow maps</LI></UL>In GLSL, arrays can be =
declared=20
using the same syntax as in C. However arrays can't be initialized when=20
declared. Accessing array's elements is done as in C.=20
<P>Structures are also allowed in GLSL. The syntax is the same as C.=20
<PRE>	struct dirlight {=0A=
		vec3 direction;=0A=
		vec3 color;=0A=
	};=0A=
</PRE>
<P>&nbsp;
<P><B>Variables</B>=20
<P>Declaring a simple variable is pretty much the same as in C, you can =
even=20
initialize a variable when declaring it.=20
<PRE>	float a,b;		// two vector (yes, the comments are like in C)=0A=
	int c =3D 2;		// c is initialized with 2=0A=
	bool d =3D true;	// d is true=0A=
</PRE>
Declaring the other types of variables follows the same pattern, but =
there are=20
differences between GLSL and C regarding initialization. GLSL relies =
heavily on=20
constructor for initialization and type casting. =20
<PRE>	float b =3D 2;		// incorrect, there is no automatic type casting=0A=
	=0A=
	float e =3D (float)2;// incorrect, requires constructors for type =
casting=0A=
	=0A=
	int a =3D 2;=0A=
	float c =3D float(a); // correct. c is 2.0=0A=
=0A=
	vec3 f;		// declaring f as a vec3=0A=
	vec3 g =3D vec3(1.0,2.0,3.0); // declaring and initializing g=0A=
	=0A=
</PRE>
GLSL is pretty flexible when initializing variables using other =
variables. All=20
that it requires is that you provide the necessary number of components. =
Look at=20
the following examples.=20
<PRE>	vec2 a =3D vec2(1.0,2.0);=0A=
	vec2 b =3D vec2(3.0,4.0);=0A=
	=0A=
	vec4 c =3D vec4(a,b) // c =3D vec4(1.0,2.0,3.0,4.0);=0A=
	=0A=
	vec2 g =3D vec2(1.0,2.0);=0A=
	float h =3D 3.0;=0A=
	=0A=
	vec3 j =3D vec3(g,h);=0A=
</PRE>
Matrices also follow this pattern. You have a wide variety of =
constructors for=20
matrices. For instance the following constructors for initializing a =
matrix are=20
available:=20
<PRE>	mat4 m =3D mat4(1.0) // initializing the diagonal of the matrix =
with 1.0=0A=
	=0A=
	vec2 a =3D vec2(1.0,2.0);=0A=
	vec2 b =3D vec2(3.0,4.0);=0A=
	=0A=
	mat2 n =3D mat2(a,b); // matrices are assigned in column major order=0A=
	=0A=
	mat2 k =3D mat2(1.0,0.0,1.0,0.0); // all elements are specified=0A=
</PRE>=09
The declaration and initialization of structures is demonstrated below:=20
<PRE>	struct dirlight {		// type definition=0A=
		vec3 direction;=0A=
		vec3 color;=0A=
	};=0A=
=0A=
	dirlight d1;=0A=
	dirlight d2 =3D dirlight(vec3(1.0,1.0,0.0),vec3(0.8,0.8,0.4));=0A=
</PRE>
In GLSL a few extras are provided to simplify our lives, and make the =
code a=20
little bit clearer. Accessing a vector can be done using letters as well =
as=20
standard C selectors. =20
<PRE>	vec4 a =3D vec4(1.0,2.0,3.0,4.0);=0A=
	=0A=
	float posX =3D a.x;=0A=
	float posY =3D a[1];=0A=
	=0A=
	vec2 posXY =3D a.xy;=0A=
	=0A=
	float depth =3D a.w=0A=
</PRE>
As shown in the previous code snippet, it is possible to use the letters =
x,y,z,w=20
to access vectors components. If you're talking about colors then =
r,g,b,a can be=20
used. For texture coordinates the available selectors are s,t,p,q. =
Notice that=20
by convention, texture coordinates are often referred as s,t,r,q. =
However=20
<I>r</I> is already being used as a selector for "red" in RGBA. Hence =
there was=20
a need to find a different letter, and the lucky one was <I>p</I>.=20
<P>Matrix selectors can take one or two arguments, for instance m[0], or =

m[2][3]. In the first case the first column is selected, whereas in the =
second a=20
single element is selected.=20
<P>As for structures the names of the elements of the structure can be =
used as=20
in C, so assuming the structures described above the following line of =
code=20
could be written: =20
<PRE>	d1.direction =3D vec3(1.0,1.0,1.0);=0A=
</PRE>
<P>&nbsp;
<P><B>Variable Qualifiers</B>=20
<P>Qualifiers give a special meaning to the variable. The following =
qualifiers=20
are available: </P></A>
<UL><A name=3D"data" a=3D"" <=3D"">=20
  <LI>const - The declaration is of a compile time constant
  <P></P></LI></A>
  <LI><A name=3D"data" a=3D"" <=3D"">attribute - Global variables that =
may change per=20
  vertex, that are passed from the OpenGL application to vertex shaders. =
This=20
  qualifier can only be used in vertex shaders. For the shader this is a =

  read-only variable. See <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#oglattribute">Attribute</A>=20
  section
  <P></P></LI>
  <LI>uniform - Global variables that may change per primitive (may not =
be set=20
  inside glBegin,/glEnd), that are passed from the OpenGL application to =
the=20
  shaders. This qualifier can be used in both vertex and fragment =
shaders. For=20
  the shaders this is a read-only variable. See <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogluniform">Uniform</A>=20
  section
  <P></P></LI>
  <LI>varying - used for interpolated data between a vertex shader and a =

  fragment shader. Available for writing in the vertex shader, and =
read-only in=20
  a fragment shader. See <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#varying">Varying</A>=20
  section
  <P>.</P></LI></UL>
<H2>Statements and Functions </H2><BR><B>Control Flow Statements</B>
<P> The available options are pretty much the same as in C. There are=20
conditional statements, like if-else, iteration statements like for, =
while and=20
do-while.=20
<PRE>	if (bool expression) =0A=
		...=0A=
	else=0A=
		...=0A=
		=0A=
		=0A=
	for (initialization; bool expression; loop expression)=0A=
		...=0A=
=0A=
	while (bool expression)=0A=
		...=0A=
		=0A=
	do =0A=
		...=0A=
	while (bool expression)=0A=
</PRE>
Although these are already available in the specification of GLSL, only =
the=20
<I>if</I> statement is commonly available in current hardware.=20
<P>A few jumps are also defined:=20
<UL>
  <LI>continue - available in loops, causes a jump to the next iteration =
of the=20
  loop
  <P></P></LI>
  <LI>break - available in loops, causes an exit of the loop
  <P></P></LI>
  <LI>discard
  <P></P></LI></UL>The discard keyword can only be used in fragment =
shaders. It=20
causes the termination of the shader for the current fragment without =
writing to=20
the frame buffer, or depth.=20
<P>&nbsp;
<P><B>Functions</B>
<P>As in C a shader is structured in functions. At least each type of =
shader=20
must have a main function declared with the following syntax:=20
<PRE>	void main()=0A=
</PRE>User defined functions may be defined. As in C a=20
function may have a return value, and should use the return statement to =
pass=20
out its result. A function can be void of course. The return type can =
have any=20
<A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.php#data">type</A>,=20
but it can't be an array.=20
<P>The parameters of a function have the following qualifiers available: =

<UL>
  <LI>in - for input parameters</LI>
  <LI>out - for outputs of the function. The return statement is also an =
option=20
  for sending the result of a function.</LI>
  <LI>inout - for parameters that are both input and output of a=20
function</LI></UL>If no qualifier is specified, by default it is =
considered to=20
be <I>in</I>.=20
<P>A few final notes: =20
<UL>
  <LI>1. A function can be overloaded as long as the list of parameters =
is=20
  different.
  <P></P></LI>
  <LI>2. Recursion behavior is undefined by specification.
  <P></P></LI></UL>An example of a function concludes this subsection.=20
<PRE>	vec4 toonify(in float intensity) {=0A=
	=0A=
		vec4 color;=0A=
	=0A=
		if (intensity &gt; 0.98)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.8,0.8,0.8,1.0);=0A=
		else if (intensity &gt; 0.5)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.4,0.4,0.8,1.0);	=0A=
		else if (intensity &gt; 0.25)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.2,0.2,0.4,1.0);=0A=
		else=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.1,0.1,0.1,1.0);		=0A=
	=0A=
		return(color);=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<P><A name=3D"varying"></A>=20
<H2>Varying Variables </H2><BR>As mentioned before we have two types of =
shaders:=20
vertex and fragment shaders. In order to compute values per fragment it =
is often=20
required to access vertex interpolated data. For instance, when =
performing=20
lighting computation per fragment, we need to access the normal at the =
fragment.=20
However in OpenGL, the normals are only specified per vertex. These =
normals are=20
accessible to the vertex shader, but not to the fragment shader since =
they come=20
from the OpenGL application as an <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#oglattribute">attribute</A>=20
variable.=20
<P>After the vertices, including all the vertex data, are processed they =
move on=20
to the next stage of the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#pipeline">pipeline</A>=20
(which still remains fixed functionality) where connectivity information =
is=20
available. It is in this stage that the primitives are assembled and =
fragments=20
computed. For each fragment there is a set of variables that are =
interpolated=20
automatically and provided to the fragment shader. An example is the =
color of=20
the fragment. The color that arrives at the fragment shader is the =
result of the=20
interpolation of the colors of the vertices that make up the primitive.=20
<P>This type of variables, where the fragment receives interpolated, =
data are=20
"varying variables". GLSL has some predefined varying variables, such as =
the=20
above mentioned color. GLSL also allows user defined varying variables. =
These=20
must be declared in both the vertex and fragment shaders, for instance:=20
<PRE>	varying float intensity;=0A=
</PRE>
<P>A varying variable must be written on a vertex shader, where we =
compute the=20
value of the variable for each vertex. In the fragment shader the =
variable,=20
whose value results from an interpolation of the vertex values computed=20
previously, can only be read.=20
<P>
