<P><A name=3D"minimal"></A>=20
<H2>    Hello World in GLSL </H2><BR>This is kind of a Hello World for =
GLSL. A=20
minimal shader that performs the most basic tasks: transform the =
vertices and=20
render the primitives in a single color. In here it this shaders, vertex =
and=20
fragment, are presented.=20
<P>&nbsp;
<P><B>Vertex Shader</B>
<P>As mentioned <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#vertexp">before</A>,=20
a vertex shader is responsible for transforming the vertices. In here it =
will be=20
shown how to transform the vertices following the equations for the =
fixed=20
functionality.=20
<P>The fixed functionality states that a vertex is to be transformed by =
the=20
modelview and projection matrices using the following equation:=20
<PRE>	vTrans =3D projection * modelview * incomingVertex=0A=
</PRE>In order to write=20
such a statement in GLSL it is necessary to access the OpenGL state to =
retrieve=20
both matrices. As mentioned before, part of the OpenGL state is =
accessible in=20
GLSL, namely the above mentioned matrices. The matrices are provided =
through=20
predefined <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogluniform">uniform</A>=20
variables declared as:=20
<PRE>	uniform mat4 gl_ModelViewMatrix;=0A=
	uniform mat4 gl_ProjectionMatrix;=0A=
</PRE>
One more thing is needed: to access the incoming vertex. These vertices =
are=20
suplied, one by one, to the vertex shader through a predefined <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#oglattribute">attribute</A>=20
variable:=20
<PRE>	attribute vec4 gl_Vertex;=0A=
</PRE>In order to output the transformed vertex,=20
the shader <U>must</U> write to the also predefined variable =
<I>gl_Position</I>,=20
declared as a vec4.=20
<P>Given the above, it is now possible to write a vertex shader that =
will do=20
nothing more than transform vertices. Note that all other functionality =
will be=20
lost, meaning, for instance, that lighting computations will not be =
performed.=20
<P> The vertex shader has to have a main function. The following code =
does the=20
trick:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	void main()=0A=
	{	=0A=
			=0A=
		gl_Position =3D gl_ProjectionMatrix * gl_ModelViewMatrix * gl_Vertex;=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>In the above code, the projection matrix is multiplied by the =
modelview=20
matrix for every vertex, which is a clear waste of time since these =
matrices do=20
not change per vertex. The matrices are <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogluniform">uniform</A>=20
variables.=20
<P>GLSL provides some derived matrices, namely the=20
<I>gl_ModelViewProjectionMatrix</I> that is the result of multiplying =
the above=20
matrices. So the vertex shader could be written as:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	void main()=0A=
	{	=0A=
			=0A=
		gl_Position =3D gl_ModelViewProjectionMatrix * gl_Vertex;=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The end result is of course the same. Does this guarantee the same=20
transformation as in the fixed functionality? Well in theory yes, but in =

practice the process of transforming the vertices may not follow the =
same order=20
as in here. This is normally a highly optimized task in a graphic card, =
and a=20
special function is provided to take advantage of that optimization. =
Another=20
reason for this function is due to the limit in the precision of the =
float data=20
type. When calculus is done in different orders, different results may =
be=20
obtained due to this limited precision. Hence the GLSL provides a =
function that=20
guarantees that not only the best performance is obtained but also that =
the=20
result is always the same as when using the fixed functionality. This =
magical=20
function is:=20
<PRE>	vec4 ftransform(void);=0A=
</PRE>This function returns the transformed=20
incoming vertex, following the same steps as the fixed functionality =
does. The=20
shader could then be rewritten as:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	void main()=0A=
	{	=0A=
			=0A=
		gl_Position =3D ftransform();=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>
<P>&nbsp;
<P><B>Fragment Shader</B>=20
<P>The fragment shader also has a predefined variable to write the color =
of the=20
fragment: <I>gl_FragColor</I>. As in the case of vertex shaders, =
fragment=20
shaders must also have a main function. The following code is for a =
fragment=20
shader that draws all fragments in a bluish color:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
		gl_FragColor =3D vec4(0.4,0.4,0.8,1.0);=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The source code for this example can be obtained in here: <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/glutglsl5_2.0.zip">OpenGL=20
2.0 syntax</A>.=20
<P><A name=3D"color"></A>=20
<H2>Color Shader </H2><BR>GLSL has access to part of the OpenGL state. =
In this=20
tutorial we'll see how to access the color as set in an OpenGL =
application with=20
<I>glColor</I>.=20
<P>GLSL has an <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#oglattribute">attribute</A>=20
variable where it keeps track of the current color. It also provides <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#varying">varying</A>=20
variables to get the color from the vertex shader to the fragment shader =

<PRE>	attribute vec4 gl_Color;=0A=
	=0A=
	varying vec4 gl_FrontColor; // writable on the vertex shader=0A=
	varying vec4 gl_BackColor; // writable on the vertex shader=0A=
	=0A=
	varying vec4 gl_Color; // readable on the fragment shader=0A=
</PRE>
The idea is as follows:=20
<OL>
  <LI>The OpenGL applications sends a color using the glColor function
  <P></P></LI>
  <LI>The vertex shader receives the color value in the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#oglattribute">attribute</A>=20
  gl_Color
  <P></P></LI>
  <LI>The vertex shader computes the front face and back face colors, =
and stores=20
  them in gl_FrontColor, and gl_BackColor respectively
  <P></P></LI>
  <LI>The fragment shader receives an interpolated color in the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#varying">varying</A>=20
  variable gl_Color, depending on the orientation of the current =
primitive, i.e.=20
  the interpolation is done using either the gl_FrontColor or the =
gl_BackColor=20
  values.
  <P></P></LI>
  <LI>The fragment shader sets gl_FragColor based on the value of =
gl_Color
  <P></P></LI></OL>This is an exception to the "rule" where a <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#varying">varying</A>=20
variable should be declared with the same name both in the vertex shader =
and the=20
fragment shader. The concept in here is that we have two variables in =
the vertex=20
shader, namely <I>gl_FrontColor</I> and <I>gl_BackColor</I>, and these =
are used=20
to derive automatically the value of gl_Color depending in the =
orientation of=20
the current face. Note that there is no conflict between the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#oglattribute">attribute</A>=20
gl_Color and the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#varying">varying</A>=20
variable gl_Color, since the former is visible only in the vertex =
shader, and=20
the latter in the fragment shader.=20
<P>Enough talk, the code for the vertex shader, where only the front =
face color=20
is computed is:=20
<HR>

<PRE>void main()=0A=
{=0A=
	gl_FrontColor =3D gl_Color;=0A=
=0A=
	gl_Position =3D ftransform();=0A=
} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The fragment shader is also a very simple shader:=20
<HR>

<PRE>void main()=0A=
{	=0A=
	gl_FragColor =3D gl_Color;=0A=
} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>
Source code based on GLUT and GLEW is available in here: <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/colorglut_2.0.zip">OpenGL=20
2.0 syntax</A>.=20
<P><A name=3D"flatten"></A>=20
<H2>Flatten Shader </H2><BR>Shader programming sets us free to explore =
new=20
effects. This is a small example just to show that with shader =
programming=20
vertices can be manipulated in strange ways.=20
<P>First we're going to flatten a 3D model, by setting its z coordinate =
to zero=20
prior to applying the modelview transformation. The source code for the =
vertex=20
shader is:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	void main(void)=0A=
	{=0A=
		vec4 v =3D vec4(gl_Vertex);		=0A=
		v.z =3D 0.0;=0A=
		=0A=
		gl_Position =3D gl_ModelViewProjectionMatrix * v;=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>First notice that we had to copy the <I>gl_Vertex</I> variable to a =
local=20
variable. The <I>gl_Vertex</I> is an <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#oglattribute">attribute</A>=20
variable provided by GLSL, and hence it is a read only variable as far =
as the=20
vertex shader is concerned. Hence to change the values of the incoming =
vertex=20
coordinates we had to copy it first to the local variable <I>v</I>.=20
<P>The fragment shader only sets a color, so it's basically the same as =
the one=20
presented in the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#minimal">Hello=20
World</A> section.=20
<P>This shader sets the z coordinate of each vertex that is processed to =
zero.=20
When applied to the teapot, the result is something like the following =
pictures=20
taken around the flattened teapot:=20
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE>
  <TBODY>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><IMG width=3D"189" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/flatten6.gif">=20
    </TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"166" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/flatten5.gif">=20
    </TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"132" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/flatten2.gif">=20
    </TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"113" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/flatten4.gif">=20
    </TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></CENTER>OK, let's play some more, now =
we're going to=20
apply a sine function to the z coordinate, as a function of the x =
coordinate, so=20
the teapot appears wavy.=20
<HR>

<PRE>	void main(void)=0A=
	{=0A=
		vec4 v =3D vec4(gl_Vertex);		=0A=
		v.z =3D sin(5.0*v.x )*0.25;=0A=
		=0A=
		gl_Position =3D gl_ModelViewProjectionMatrix * v;=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE>
  <TBODY>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><IMG width=3D"197" height=3D"125" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/flattsine1.gif">=20
    </TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"208" height=3D"125" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/flattsine2.gif">=20
    </TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"174" height=3D"125" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/flattsine3.gif">=20
    </TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"180" height=3D"125" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/flattsine4.gif">=20
    </TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></CENTER>And finally to end this simple =
example we're=20
going to add some vertex animation. In order to do this we need a =
variable to=20
keep track of time, or a frame counter. A vertex shader can't keep track =
of=20
values between vertices, let alone between frames. Therefore we need to =
define=20
this variable in the OpenGL application, and pass it to the shader as a =
uniform=20
variable. Let's assume that there is a frame counter in the OpenGL =
application=20
named "time", and that in the shader there is an <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogluniform">uniform</A>=20
attribute with the same name.=20
<P>The code for the vertex shader becomes something like:=20
<HR>

<PRE>uniform float time;=0A=
=0A=
void main(void)=0A=
{=0A=
	vec4 v =3D vec4(gl_Vertex);=0A=
	=0A=
	v.z =3D sin(5.0*v.x + time*0.01)*0.25;=0A=
=0A=
	gl_Position =3D gl_ModelViewProjectionMatrix * v;=0A=
} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>As mentioned in the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogluniform">Uniform=20
Variables</A> section, in the OpenGL application two steps are required: =
=20
<UL>
  <LI>setup: getting the location of the uniform variable</LI>
  <LI>render: update the uniform variable</LI></UL>The setup phase is =
only:=20
<PRE>	loc =3D glGetUniformLocation(p,"time");=0A=
</PRE>
<P>Where p is the handler to the program, and "time" is the name of the =
uniform=20
variable as defined in the vertex shader. The variable <I>loc</I> is of =
type=20
GLint and should be defined in a place where it is also accessible to =
the render=20
function.=20
<P>The render function could be something like:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	void renderScene(void) {=0A=
	=0A=
		glClear(GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT | GL_DEPTH_BUFFER_BIT);=0A=
	=0A=
		glLoadIdentity();=0A=
		gluLookAt(0.0,0.0,5.0, =0A=
			0.0,0.0,0.0,=0A=
			0.0f,1.0f,0.0f);=0A=
	=0A=
		glUniform1f(loc, time);=0A=
	=0A=
		glutSolidTeapot(1);=0A=
		time+=3D0.01;=0A=
	=0A=
		glutSwapBuffers();=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>where the variable <I>time</I> is initialized to some value in the=20
initialization, and is incremented in each frame. =20
<P>The source code for this last example, together with the shaders can =
be=20
obtained  in here: <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/flatten_2.0.zip">OpenGL=20
2.0 syntax</A>.=20
<P>Note: you'll need to have <A =
href=3D"http://glew.sourceforge.net/">glew</A> to=20
run this. A <A href=3D"http://www.typhoonlabs.com/">Shader Designer</A> =
project is=20
also available in <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/flattensd.zip">here</A>.=20
A mpeg showing the effect can be downloaded <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/images/flattensg.mpg">here</A>.=20
This video was produced using a feature on <A=20
href=3D"http://www.typhoonlabs.com/">Shader Designer</A> that creates an =
AVI=20
movie, and afterwards it was converted to MPEG using <A =
href=3D"http://fxmpegwriter.com/">Fx=20
Mpeg Writer Free version</A>. <A name=3D"toon" a=3D"" <=3D""></A>
<H2><A name=3D"toon" a=3D"" <=3D"">Toon Shading </A></H2><A =
name=3D"toon" a=3D"" <=3D""><BR>
Toon shading is probably the simplest non-photorealistic shader we can =
write. It=20
uses very few colors, usually tones, hence it changes abruptly from tone =
to=20
tone, yet it provides a sense of 3D to the model. The following image =
shows what=20
we're trying to achieve.=20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"300" height=3D"200" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/toonexample.gif">=20
</CENTER>The tones in the teapot above are selected based on the angle, =
actually=20
on the cosine of the angle, between a virtual light's direction and the =
normal=20
of the surface. =20
<P>So if we have a normal that is close to the light's direction, then =
we'll use=20
the brightest tone. As the angle between the normal and the light's =
direction=20
increases darker tones will be used. In other words, the cosine of the =
angle=20
provides an intensity for the tone.=20
<P>In this tutorial we'll start with a version that computes the =
intensity per=20
vertex. Then we will move this computation to the fragment shader. It =
will also=20
be shown how to access OpenGL light's position.=20
<P>
<H2>Toon Shading - Version I </H2><BR></A>
<P><A name=3D"toon" a=3D"" <=3D""> The first version presented in here =
computes an=20
intensity per vertex. Then the fragment shader uses the vertex =
interpolated=20
intensity to compute a tone for the fragment. The vertex shader must =
therefore=20
declare a <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#varying">varying</A>=20
variable to store the intensity. The fragment shader must declare the =
same=20
variable, also using the varying qualifier, to receive the properly =
interpolated=20
value for the intensity.=20
<P>The light direction could be defined in the vertex shader as a local =
variable=20
or as a constant, however having it as a <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogluniform">uniform</A>=20
variable provides more freedom since it can be set arbitrarily on the =
OpenGL=20
application. The light's direction variable will be defined in the =
shader as=20
<PRE>	uniform vec3 lightDir;=0A=
</PRE>
<P>For now, lets assume that the light's direction is defined in world =
space.=20
<P>The vertex shader has access to the normals, as specified in the =
OpenGL=20
application, through the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#oglattribute">attribute</A>=20
variable <I>gl_Normal</I>. This is the normal as defined in the OpenGL=20
application with the <I>glNormal</I> function, hence in model local =
space.=20
<P>If no rotations or scales are performed on the model in the OpenGL=20
application, then the normal defined in world space, provided to the =
vertex=20
shader as <I>gl_Normal</I>,  coincides with the normal defined in the =
local=20
space. The normal is a direction and therefore it is not affected by=20
translations.=20
<P>Because both the normal and the light's direction are specified in =
the same=20
space, the vertex shader can jump directly to the cosine computation =
between the=20
light's direction, i.e. lightDir, and the normal. The cosine can be =
computed=20
using the following formula=20
<PRE>	cos(lightDir,normal) =3D lightDir . normal / ( |lightDir| * =
|normal| )=0A=
</PRE>
where "." is the inner product, aka as the dot product. This can be =
simplified=20
if both the normal and lightDir are normalized, i.e.=20
<PRE>	| normal | =3D 1=0A=
	| lightDir | =3D 1=0A=
</PRE>Hence if these two conditions are=20
guaranteed the computation for the cosine can be simplified to=20
<PRE>	cos(lightDir,normal) =3D lightDir . normal =0A=
</PRE>Since the variable=20
lightDir is supplied by the OpenGL application we can assume that it =
arrives at=20
the shader already normalized. It would be a waste of time having to =
normalize=20
it for every vertex, instead of performing it only when the lightDir =
changes.=20
Also it is reasonable to expect that the normals from the OpenGL =
application are=20
normalized.=20
<P>Therefore the cosine, which we will store in a variable named =
intensity, can=20
be computed with the <I>dot</I> function provided by GLSL.=20
<PRE>	intensity =3D dot(lightDir, gl_Normal);=0A=
</PRE>
<P>The only thing that's left to do in the vertex shader is to transform =
the=20
vertex coordinates. The complete code for the shader is as follows:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	uniform vec3 lightDir;=0A=
	=0A=
	varying float intensity;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
		vec3 ld;=0A=
		=0A=
		intensity =3D dot(lightDir,gl_Normal);=0A=
		=0A=
		gl_Position =3D ftransform();=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>Now, in the fragment shader, all that's left to do is to define a =
color for=20
the fragment based on the intensity. The intensity must be passed on to =
the=20
fragment shader, since it is the fragment shader that is responsible for =
setting=20
the colors for fragments. As mentioned before, the intensity will be =
defined as=20
a <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#varying">varying</A>=20
variable on both shaders, hence it must be written in the vertex shader =
for the=20
fragment shader to read it.=20
<P>The color can be computed in the fragment shader as follows:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	vec4 color;=0A=
	=0A=
	if (intensity &gt; 0.95)=0A=
		color =3D vec4(1.0,0.5,0.5,1.0);=0A=
	else if (intensity &gt; 0.5)=0A=
		color =3D vec4(0.6,0.3,0.3,1.0);=0A=
	else if (intensity &gt; 0.25)=0A=
		color =3D vec4(0.4,0.2,0.2,1.0);=0A=
	else=0A=
		color =3D vec4(0.2,0.1,0.1,1.0);=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>As can be seen from the code above, the brightest color is used when =
the=20
cosine is larger than 0.95 and the darker color is used for cosines =
smaller than=20
0.25. All there is left to do in the fragment shader is to set the=20
<I>gl_FragColor</I> based on the <I>color</I>. The code for the fragment =
shader=20
is:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	varying float intensity;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
		vec4 color;=0A=
		=0A=
		if (intensity &gt; 0.95)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(1.0,0.5,0.5,1.0);=0A=
		else if (intensity &gt; 0.5)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.6,0.3,0.3,1.0);=0A=
		else if (intensity &gt; 0.25)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.4,0.2,0.2,1.0);=0A=
		else=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.2,0.1,0.1,1.0);=0A=
	=0A=
		gl_FragColor =3D color;=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The following image shows the end result, and it doesn't look very =
nice does=20
it? The main problem is that we're interpolating the intensity. This is =
not the=20
same as computing the intensity with the proper normal for the fragment. =
Go on=20
to the next section to see toon shading done properly!=20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"360" height=3D"250" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/toonv.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>
<H2>Toon Shader - Version II </H2><BR>GLSL has access to part of the =
OpenGL=20
state. In this tutorial we'll see how to access the color as set in an =
OpenGL=20
application with <I>glColor</I>.=20
<P>GLSL has an <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#oglattribute">attribute</A>=20
variable where it keeps track of the current color. In this section we =
will do=20
the toon shader effect per fragment. In order to do that, we need to =
have access=20
to the fragments normal per fragment. Hence the vertex shader only needs =
to=20
write the normal into a <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#varying">varying</A>=20
variable, so that the fragment shader has access to the interpolated =
normal.=20
<P>The vertex shader gets simplified, since the color intensity =
computation will=20
now be done in the fragment shader. The <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogluniform">uniform</A>=20
variable <I>lightDir</I> also has moved to the fragment shader, since it =
is no=20
longer used in the vertex shader.  See the code bellow for the new =
vertex=20
shader:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	varying vec3 normal;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
		normal =3D gl_Normal;=0A=
	=0A=
		gl_Position =3D ftransform();=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>In the fragment shader we now need to declare the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogluniform">uniform</A>=20
variable <I>lightDir</I> since the intensity is based on this variable. =
A=20
varying variable is also defined to receive the interpolated normal. The =
code=20
for the fragment shader then becomes:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	uniform vec3 lightDir;=0A=
	=0A=
	varying vec3 normal;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
	=0A=
		float intensity;=0A=
		vec4 color;=0A=
		=0A=
		intensity =3D dot(lightDir,normal);=0A=
		=0A=
		if (intensity &gt; 0.95)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(1.0,0.5,0.5,1.0);=0A=
		else if (intensity &gt; 0.5)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.6,0.3,0.3,1.0);=0A=
		else if (intensity &gt; 0.25)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.4,0.2,0.2,1.0);=0A=
		else=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.2,0.1,0.1,1.0);=0A=
		=0A=
		gl_FragColor =3D color;=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>And the result is:=20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"360" height=3D"250" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/toonv.gif">=20
</CENTER>No, its not a bug! Its the same result as in the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#toon1">previous</A>=20
section. So what happened?=20
<P>Let's look closely at the differences between the two versions. In =
the first=20
version we computed an intensity in the vertex shader and used the =
interpolated=20
value in the fragment shader. In the second version we interpolated the =
normal,=20
in the vertex shader, for the fragment shader where we computed the dot =
product.=20
 Interpolation and dot product are both linear operations, so it doesn't =
matter=20
if we compute the dot product first and then interpolate, or if we =
interpolate=20
first and then compute the dot product.=20
<P>What is wrong in here is the usage of the interpolated normal for the =
dot=20
product in the fragment shader! And it is wrong because the normal, =
although it=20
has the right direction, it most likely has a not unit length.=20
<P>We know that the direction is right because we assumed that the =
normals that=20
arrived at the vertex shader were normalized, and interpolating =
normalized=20
vectors, provides a vector with the correct direction. However the =
length is=20
wrong in the general case because interpolating normalized normals only =
yields a=20
unit length vector if the normals being interpolated have the same =
direction,=20
which is highly unlikely in smooth surfaces. See <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#normalization">Normalization=20
Issues</A> for more details.=20
<P>The main reason to move the intensity computation from the vertex =
shader to=20
the fragment shader was to compute it using the proper normal for the =
fragment.=20
We have a normal vector that has the correct direction but is not unit =
length.=20
In order to fix this all we have to do is to normalize the incoming =
normal=20
vector at the fragment shader. The following code is the correct and =
complete=20
toon shader:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	uniform vec3 lightDir;=0A=
	=0A=
	varying vec3 normal;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
	=0A=
		float intensity;=0A=
		vec4 color;=0A=
=0A=
		=0A=
		intensity =3D dot(lightDir,normalize(normal));=0A=
		=0A=
		if (intensity &gt; 0.95)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(1.0,0.5,0.5,1.0);=0A=
		else if (intensity &gt; 0.5)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.6,0.3,0.3,1.0);=0A=
		else if (intensity &gt; 0.25)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.4,0.2,0.2,1.0);=0A=
		else=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.2,0.1,0.1,1.0);=0A=
		=0A=
		gl_FragColor =3D color;=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The result for this version of the toon shader is depicted below. It =
looks=20
nicer, yet it is not perfect. It suffers from aliasing, but this is =
outside the=20
scope of this tutorial ;) =20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"440" height=3D"280" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/toonf.gif">=20
</CENTER>In the next section we will use an OpenGL light to set the =
light's=20
direction of the shader.=20
<P>
<H2>Toon Shading - Version III </H2><BR>Before we finish this tutorial =
there is=20
just one more thing: we're going to use an OpenGL light instead of the =
variable=20
lightDir. In this way we can define a light in the OpenGL application =
and use=20
that light's direction in our shader. Note: it is not necessary to turn =
on the=20
lights using <I>glEnable</I>, since we are not going to apply the light =
in=20
OpenGL.=20
<P>We shall assume that the first light (GL_LIGHT0) in the OpenGL =
application is=20
a directional light.=20
<P>GLSL provides access to part of the OpenGL state, namely the lights=20
properties. GLSL declares a C type struct for the lights properties, and =
an=20
array to store these properties for each of the lights.=20
<HR>

<PRE>struct gl_LightSourceParameters {=0A=
	vec4 ambient; =0A=
	vec4 diffuse; =0A=
	vec4 specular; =0A=
	vec4 position; =0A=
	...=0A=
};=0A=
=0A=
uniform gl_LightSourceParameters gl_LightSource[gl_MaxLights];=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>This means that we can access the light's direction (using the=20
<I>position</I> field of a directional light) in the vertex shader. =
Again we=20
shall assume that the light's direction is normalized by the OpenGL =
application.=20
=20
<P>The OpenGL specification states that when a light position is set it =
is=20
automatically converted to eye space coordinates, i.e. camera =
coordinates.  We=20
can assume that the light position stays normalized when automatically =
converted=20
to eye space. This will be true if we the upper left 3x3 sub matrix of =
the=20
modelview matrix is orthogonal (this is ensured if we set the camera =
using=20
gluLookAt, and we don't use scales in our application). =20
<P>We have to convert the normal to eye space coordinates as well to =
compute the=20
dot product, as it only makes sense to compute angles, or cosines in =
this case,=20
between vectors in the same space, and as mentioned before the light =
position is=20
stored in eye coordinates.=20
<P>To transform the normal to eye space we will use the pre-defined =
uniform=20
variable mat3 <I>gl_NormalMatrix</I>. This matrix is the transpose of =
the=20
inverse of the 3x3 upper left sub matrix from the modelview matrix. We =
will do=20
the normal transformation per vertex. The vertex shader then becomes:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	varying vec3 normal;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
=0A=
		normal =3D gl_NormalMatrix * gl_Normal;=0A=
	=0A=
		gl_Position =3D ftransform();=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>In the fragment shader we must access the light position to compute =
the=20
intensity:=20
<HR>

<PRE>	varying vec3 normal;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
		float intensity;=0A=
		vec4 color;=0A=
		vec3 n =3D normalize(normal);=0A=
		=0A=
		intensity =3D dot(vec3(gl_LightSource[0].position),n);=0A=
		=0A=
		if (intensity &gt; 0.95)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(1.0,0.5,0.5,1.0);=0A=
		else if (intensity &gt; 0.5)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.6,0.3,0.3,1.0);=0A=
		else if (intensity &gt; 0.25)=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.4,0.2,0.2,1.0);=0A=
		else=0A=
			color =3D vec4(0.2,0.1,0.1,1.0);=0A=
		=0A=
		gl_FragColor =3D color;=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>Source code based no GLUT and GLEW is available in here: <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/toonglut_2.0.zip">OpenGL=20
2.0 syntax</A>.=20
<P><A name=3D"lights"></A>=20
<H2>Lighting </H2><BR>In OpenGL there are three types of lights: =
directional,=20
point, and spotlight. In this tutorial we'll start to implement a =
directional=20
light. First we'll start with an implementation in GLSL that mimics the =
OpenGL=20
way of lighting. =20
<P>We'll build the shader incrementally starting with ambient light up =
to=20
specular lighting.=20
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE>
  <TBODY>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><IMG width=3D"203" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/dirambvert.gif"></TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"204" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/dirdiffvert.gif"></TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"209" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/dirvert.gif"></TD></TR>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><I>Ambient</I></TD>
    <TD><I>Ambient + Diffuse</I></TD>
    <TD><I>Specular</I></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>Then we'll move on to lighting per pixel in order to get better =
results.=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"193" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/dirpix.gif"></CENTER>
<P>Next we'll implement point and spot lights per pixel. These last =
tutorials=20
are heavily based on the directional lights tutorial because most of the =
code is=20
common.
<P>
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE>
  <TBODY>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><IMG width=3D"205" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/pointpix.gif"></TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"168" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/spotpix.gif"></TD></TR>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><I>Point Light</I></TD>
    <TD><I>Spot Light</I></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>As mentioned in the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#toon3">toon=20
shader</A> tutorial  GLSL offers access to the OpenGL state that =
contains data=20
for the light setting. This data describes the individual light's =
setting as=20
well as global parameters.=20
<PRE>	struct gl_LightSourceParameters {=0A=
		vec4 ambient; =0A=
		vec4 diffuse; =0A=
		vec4 specular; =0A=
		vec4 position; =0A=
		vec4 halfVector; =0A=
		vec3 spotDirection; =0A=
		float spotExponent; =0A=
		float spotCutoff; // (range: [0.0,90.0], 180.0)=0A=
		float spotCosCutoff; // (range: [1.0,0.0],-1.0)=0A=
		float constantAttenuation; =0A=
		float linearAttenuation; =0A=
		float quadraticAttenuation;	=0A=
	};=0A=
	=0A=
	uniform gl_LightSourceParameters gl_LightSource[gl_MaxLights];=0A=
	=0A=
	struct gl_LightModelParameters {=0A=
		vec4 ambient; =0A=
	};=0A=
	=0A=
	uniform gl_LightModelParameters gl_LightModel;=0A=
</PRE>
Material properties are accessible in GLSL as well:=20
<PRE>	struct gl_MaterialParameters {=0A=
		vec4 emission;   =0A=
		vec4 ambient;    =0A=
		vec4 diffuse;    =0A=
		vec4 specular;   =0A=
		float shininess; =0A=
	};=0A=
	=0A=
	uniform gl_MaterialParameters gl_FrontMaterial;=0A=
	uniform gl_MaterialParameters gl_BackMaterial;=0A=
</PRE>
Most of these parameters, both for lighting and materials are familiar =
to those=20
used to build applications in OpenGL. We shall use these properties to =
implement=20
our directional light.=20
<P><A name=3D"ogldir1"></A>=20
<H2>OpenGL Directional Lights I </H2><BR>The equations in here are from =
the=20
chapter "The Mathematics of Lighting" from the book "OpenGL Programming =
Guide",=20
aka the Red Book.=20
<P>We'll start with the diffuse term. The diffuse lighting in OpenGL =
assumes=20
that the light is perceived with the same intensity regardless if the =
viewers=20
position. Its intensity is proportional to both the lights diffuse =
intensity as=20
well as material's diffuse reflection coefficient. The intensity is also =

proportional to the angle between the light direction and the normal of =
the=20
surface. =20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"198" height=3D"196" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/ndotl.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P></P>The following formula is used in OpenGL to compute the diffuse =
term:=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"218" height=3D"48" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqdifflight.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>where I is the reflected intensity, Ld is the light's diffuse color=20
(<I>gl_LightSource[0].diffuse</I>), and Md is the material's diffuse =
coefficient=20
(<I>gl_FrontMaterial.diffuse</I>).=20
<P>This is known as Lambertian Reflection. 'Lambert's cosine law' states =
that=20
the brightness of a diffusely radiating plane surface is proportional to =
the=20
cosine of the angle formed by the line of sight and the normal to the =
surface.=20
This was more than 200 years ago (Johann Heinrich Lambert, 1728-1777)!=20
<P>The vertex shader to implement this formula will use the lights =
properties,=20
namely its position, and diffuse intensity. It will also use the =
materials=20
diffuse setting. Hence to use this shader just set the light as usual in =
OpenGL.=20
Note however that since we're not using the fixed functionality, there =
is no=20
need to enable the lights. =20
<P>Since we need to compute a cosine, first we're going to make sure =
that the=20
normal vector and the light direction vector =
(<I>gl_LightSource[0].position</I>)=20
are normalized, and then we'll use the dot product to get the cosine. =
Note that,=20
for directional lights, OpenGL stores the light direction as the vector =
from the=20
vertex to the light source, which is the opposite to what is shown in =
the above=20
figure.=20
<P>OpenGL stores the lights direction in eye space coordinates; hence we =
need to=20
transform the normal to eye space in order to compute the dot product. =
To=20
transform the normal to eye space we will use the pre-defined uniform =
variable=20
mat3 gl_NormalMatrix. This matrix is the transpose of the inverse of the =
3x3=20
upper left sub matrix from the modelview matrix. =20
<P>The following vertex shader shows the GLSL code to achieve this.=20
<P>
<HR>

<PRE>	void main() {=0A=
	=0A=
		vec3 normal, lightDir;=0A=
		vec4 diffuse;=0A=
		float NdotL;=0A=
		=0A=
		/* first transform the normal into eye space and normalize the result =
*/=0A=
		normal =3D normalize(gl_NormalMatrix * gl_Normal);=0A=
		=0A=
		/* now normalize the light's direction. Note that according to the=0A=
		OpenGL specification, the light is stored in eye space. Also since =0A=
		we're talking about a directional light, the position field is =
actually =0A=
		direction */=0A=
		lightDir =3D normalize(vec3(gl_LightSource[0].position));=0A=
		=0A=
		/* compute the cos of the angle between the normal and lights =
direction. =0A=
		The light is directional so the direction is constant for every vertex.=0A=
		Since these two are normalized the cosine is the dot product. We also =0A=
		need to clamp the result to the [0,1] range. */=0A=
		NdotL =3D max(dot(normal, lightDir), 0.0);=0A=
		=0A=
		/* Compute the diffuse term */=0A=
		diffuse =3D gl_FrontMaterial.diffuse * gl_LightSource[0].diffuse;=0A=
		=0A=
		gl_FrontColor =3D  NdotL * diffuse;=0A=
		=0A=
		gl_Position =3D ftransform();=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>Now in the fragment shader all there is left to do is setting the =
fragments=20
color, using the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#varying">varying</A>=20
gl_Color variable.=20
<P>
<HR>

<PRE>	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
		gl_FragColor =3D gl_Color;=0A=
	}=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The following image shows this shader applied to the teapot. Note =
that the=20
bottom of the teapot is too dark. This is because we're not taking into =
account=20
the ambient lighting terms available in OpenGL.=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"308" height=3D"192" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/dirdiffonlyvert.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>Incorporating the ambient terms is also easy to do. There is a global =
ambient=20
term and a light ambient term. The formula for the ambient term is as =
follows:=20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"234" height=3D"35" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/ambient.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>The vertex shader needs to add a few instructions to compute the =
ambient=20
term:=20
<P>
<HR>

<PRE>	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
		vec3 normal, lightDir;=0A=
		vec4 diffuse, ambient, globalAmbient;=0A=
		float NdotL;=0A=
		=0A=
		normal =3D normalize(gl_NormalMatrix * gl_Normal);=0A=
		lightDir =3D normalize(vec3(gl_LightSource[0].position));=0A=
		NdotL =3D max(dot(normal, lightDir), 0.0);=0A=
		diffuse =3D gl_FrontMaterial.diffuse * gl_LightSource[0].diffuse;=0A=
		=0A=
		/* Compute the ambient and globalAmbient terms */=0A=
		ambient =3D gl_FrontMaterial.ambient * gl_LightSource[0].ambient;=0A=
		globalAmbient =3D gl_LightModel.ambient * gl_FrontMaterial.ambient;=0A=
		=0A=
		gl_FrontColor =3D  NdotL * diffuse + globalAmbient + ambient;=0A=
		=0A=
		gl_Position =3D ftransform();=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The following image shows the end result. Adding an ambient term =
washes out=20
color, but it's a cheap workaround for the lack of a global illumination =
model=20
where light bounces, and hence it affects surfaces not directly affected =
by the=20
light source.=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"290" height=3D"192" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/dirdiffamb.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>Move on to the next section for the specular component.=20
<P>
<H2>OpenGL Directional Lights II </H2><BR>Time for the specular =
component of the=20
OpenGL directional light. The lighting model used is the Blinn-Phong =
model,=20
which is a simplification of the Phong model. We shall take a peek at =
the Phong=20
model since it makes it easier to understand the Blinn-Phong model.=20
<P>The Phong model says that the specular component is proportional to =
the=20
cosine between the light reflection vector and the eye vector. The =
following=20
image shows this graphically:=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"379" height=3D"205" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/reflectionV.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>L is the vector from the light to the vertex being shaded. N is the =
normal=20
vector, and Eye is the vector from the vertex to the eye, or camera. R =
is the=20
vector L mirror reflected on the surface. The specular component is =
proportional=20
to the cosine of alpha.=20
<P>If the eye vector coincides with the reflection vector then we get =
the=20
maximum specular intensity. As the eye vector diverges from the =
reflection=20
vector the specular intensity decays. The rate of decay is controlled by =
a=20
shininess factor. The higher the shininess factor the faster the decay. =
This=20
means that with a high shininess the bright spot caused by the specular=20
component is smaller than with a low shininess value. Simply put, the =
shininess=20
(a value between 0 and 128 in OpenGL) controls the size of the bright =
spot.=20
<P>
<TABLE>
  <TBODY>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><IMG width=3D"226" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/shine8.gif"></TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"221" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/shine64.gif"></TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"208" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/shine128.gif"></TD></TR>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><I>Shininess =3D 8</I></TD>
    <TD><I>Shininess =3D 64</I></TD>
    <TD><I>Shininess =3D 128</I></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE>
<P>The formula for the reflection vector is as follows:=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"186" height=3D"33" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqreflectV.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>And the specular component in OpenGL using the Phong model would be:=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"264" height=3D"42" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqphong.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>Where the <I>s</I> exponent is the shininess value, Ls is the lights =
specular=20
intensity, and Ms is the materials specular coefficient.=20
<P>Blinn proposed a simpler and faster model, knows as the Blinn-Phong =
model=20
that is based on the half-vector. The half-vector is a vector with a =
direction=20
half-way between the eye vector and the light vector as shown in the =
following=20
figure:=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"334" height=3D"207" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/halfV.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>The intensity of the specular component is now based on the cosine of =
the=20
angle between the half vector and the normal. The formula for the =
half-vector is=20
much simpler than for the reflection vector:=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"137" height=3D"31" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqhalfV.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>And the specular component in OpenGL using the Blinn-Phong model is:=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"256" height=3D"38" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqblinnphong.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>This is the actual stuff as commonly used in the fixed pipeline of =
the=20
graphics hardware. Since we want to emulate the OpenGL's directional =
light,=20
we're going to use this last equation in our shader. There is a good =
news:=20
OpenGL computes the half-vector for us! So the following snippet of code =
should=20
do the trick:=20
<P>
<HR>

<PRE>	/* compute the specular term if NdotL is  larger than zero */=0A=
	if (NdotL &gt; 0.0) {=0A=
	=0A=
		// normalize the half-vector, and then compute the =0A=
		// cosine (dot product) with the normal=0A=
		NdotHV =3D max(dot(normal, gl_LightSource[0].halfVector.xyz),0.0);=0A=
		specular =3D gl_FrontMaterial.specular * gl_LightSource[0].specular * =0A=
				pow(NdotHV,gl_FrontMaterial.shininess);=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The full source of the shaders, in a <A=20
href=3D"http://www.typhoonlabs.com/">Shader Designer</A> project can be =
found in=20
<A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/ogldirsd.zip">here</A>.=20
<P>
<H2>Directional Light per Pixel </H2><BR>In this  section we'll modify =
the=20
previous shaders to compute the directional light per pixel. Basically =
we're=20
going to split the work between the two shaders, so that some operations =
are=20
done per pixel.=20
<P>First lets take a look at the information we receive per vertex:=20
<UL>
  <LI>normal</LI>
  <LI>half vector</LI>
  <LI>light direction</LI></UL>We have to transform the normal to eye =
space, and=20
normalize it. We also have to normalize both the half vector and the =
light=20
direction, both of which are already in eye space. These normalized =
vectors are=20
to be interpolated and then sent to the fragment shader so we need to =
declare=20
varying variables to hold the normalized vectors. =20
<P>We can also perform some computations combining the lights settings =
with the=20
materials in the vertex shader, hence helping to split the load between =
the=20
vertex and fragment shader.=20
<P>The vertex shader could be:=20
<P>
<HR>

<PRE>	varying vec4 diffuse,ambient;=0A=
	varying vec3 normal,lightDir,halfVector;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{	=0A=
		/* first transform the normal into eye space and =0A=
		normalize the result */=0A=
		normal =3D normalize(gl_NormalMatrix * gl_Normal);=0A=
		=0A=
		/* now normalize the light's direction. Note that =0A=
		according to the OpenGL specification, the light =0A=
		is stored in eye space. Also since we're talking about =0A=
		a directional light, the position field is actually direction */=0A=
		lightDir =3D normalize(vec3(gl_LightSource[0].position));=0A=
	=0A=
		/* Normalize the halfVector to pass it to the fragment shader */=0A=
		halfVector =3D normalize(gl_LightSource[0].halfVector.xyz);=0A=
					=0A=
		/* Compute the diffuse, ambient and globalAmbient terms */=0A=
		diffuse =3D gl_FrontMaterial.diffuse * gl_LightSource[0].diffuse;=0A=
		ambient =3D gl_FrontMaterial.ambient * gl_LightSource[0].ambient;=0A=
		ambient +=3D gl_LightModel.ambient * gl_FrontMaterial.ambient;=0A=
	=0A=
		gl_Position =3D ftransform();=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>Now for the fragment shader. The same varying variables have to be =
declared.=20
We have to normalize again the normal. Note that there is no need to =
normalize=20
again the light direction. This last vector is common to all vertices =
since=20
we're talking about a directional light. The interpolation between two =
equal=20
vectors yields the same vector, so there is no need to normalize again. =
Then we=20
compute the dot product between the interpolated normalized normal and =
the light=20
direction.=20
<P>
<HR>

<PRE>	varying vec4 diffuse,ambient;=0A=
	varying vec3 normal,lightDir,halfVector;=0A=
	=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
		vec3 n,halfV;=0A=
		float NdotL,NdotHV;=0A=
		=0A=
		/* The ambient term will always be present */=0A=
		vec4 color =3D ambient;=0A=
		=0A=
		/* a fragment shader can't write a varying variable, hence we need=0A=
		a new variable to store the normalized interpolated normal */=0A=
		n =3D normalize(normal);=0A=
		=0A=
		/* compute the dot product between normal and ldir */=0A=
		NdotL =3D max(dot(n,lightDir),0.0);=0A=
	=0A=
		....=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>If the dot product <I>NdotL</I> is greater than zero then we must =
compute the=20
diffuse component, which is the diffuse setting we received from the =
vertex=20
shader multiplied by the dot product. We must also compute the specular =
term. To=20
compute the specular component we must first normalize the halfvector we =

received from the vertex shader, and also compute the dot product =
between the=20
normalized halfvector and the normal.=20
<P>
<HR>

<PRE>		...=0A=
		if (NdotL &gt; 0.0) {=0A=
			color +=3D diffuse * NdotL;=0A=
			halfV =3D normalize(halfVector);=0A=
			NdotHV =3D max(dot(n,halfV),0.0);=0A=
			color +=3D gl_FrontMaterial.specular * =0A=
					gl_LightSource[0].specular * =0A=
					pow(NdotHV, gl_FrontMaterial.shininess);=0A=
		}=0A=
	=0A=
		gl_FragColor =3D color;=0A=
}=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The following images show the difference in terms of visual results =
between=20
computing the lighting per vertex versus per pixel.  <A =
name=3D"pointlight"></A>=20
<H2>Point Light Per Pixel </H2><BR>This tutorial is based on the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogldir1">directional=20
lights tutorial</A> as most (99%) of the code comes from there. The =
tutorial is=20
based on the difference between a directional light and a point light. A =

directional light is assumed to be infinitely far away, so that the =
light rays=20
are parallel when they reach the object. In contrast, a point light has =
a=20
position, and sends rays in all directions. Furthermore, in a point =
light, the=20
intensity decays with the distance to the vertex.=20
<P>From an OpenGL application point of view there are two differences =
between=20
the two:=20
<UL>
  <LI>the <I>w</I> component of the light position field: in a =
directional light=20
  it is zero to indicate that the position is in fact a direction (or =
vector),=20
  where as in a point light the <I>w</I> component of the light position =
field=20
  is 1.</LI>
  <LI>The attenuation is specified based on three coefficients: a =
constant term,=20
  a linear term, and a quadratic term</LI></UL>
<P>From a computational point of view these differences must be taken =
care of.=20
For a directional light, the direction of the light rays is constant for =
every=20
vertex, whereas for a point light it is the vector from the vertex to =
the lights=20
position. Hence, all that needs to change in the vertex shader is the=20
computation of the lights direction.  =20
<P>The attenuation is computed based on the following formula in OpenGL: =

<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"214" height=3D"71" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqatt.gif"></CENTER>
<P>where k0 is the constant attenuation, k1 is the linear attenuation, =
k2 is the=20
quadratic attenuation and d is the distance from the light's position to =
the=20
vertex.=20
<P>Note that the attenuation does not vary linearly with distance, hence =
we=20
can't compute the attenuation per vertex and use the interpolated value =
in the=20
fragment shader. We can however compute the distance in the vertex =
shader and=20
use the interpolated distance in the fragment shader to compute the =
attenuation.=20
<P>The equation for the color using a point light is:=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"576" height=3D"36" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqpointlight.gif"></CENTER>
<P>As shown in the above equation, the ambient term must be spitted in =
two: one=20
global ambient term using the lighting model ambient setting and a light =

specific ambient term. The vertex shader must separate the computation =
of the=20
ambient term accordingly. The new vertex shader is:=20
<P>
<HR>

<PRE>	varying vec4 diffuse,ambientGlobal,ambient;=0A=
	varying vec3 normal,lightDir,halfVector;=0A=
	varying float dist;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{	=0A=
		vec4 ecPos;=0A=
		vec3 aux;=0A=
		=0A=
		normal =3D normalize(gl_NormalMatrix * gl_Normal);=0A=
		=0A=
		/* these are the new lines of code to compute the light's direction */=0A=
		ecPos =3D gl_ModelViewMatrix * gl_Vertex;=0A=
		aux =3D vec3(gl_LightSource[0].position-ecPos);=0A=
		lightDir =3D normalize(aux);=0A=
		dist =3D length(aux);=0A=
	=0A=
		halfVector =3D normalize(gl_LightSource[0].halfVector.xyz);=0A=
		=0A=
		/* Compute the diffuse, ambient and globalAmbient terms */=0A=
		diffuse =3D gl_FrontMaterial.diffuse * gl_LightSource[0].diffuse;=0A=
		=0A=
		/* The ambient terms have been separated since one of them */=0A=
		/* suffers attenuation */=0A=
		ambient =3D gl_FrontMaterial.ambient * gl_LightSource[0].ambient;=0A=
		ambientGlobal =3D gl_LightModel.ambient * gl_FrontMaterial.ambient;=0A=
		=0A=
			=0A=
		gl_Position =3D ftransform();=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The fragment shader needs to compute the attenuation. It also needs =
to=20
normalize the interpolated light direction, since the direction is =
potentially=20
different for every vertex.=20
<P>
<HR>

<PRE>	varying vec4 diffuse,ambientGlobal, ambient;=0A=
	varying vec3 normal,lightDir,halfVector;=0A=
	varying float dist;=0A=
	=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
		vec3 n,halfV,viewV,ldir;=0A=
		float NdotL,NdotHV;=0A=
		vec4 color =3D ambientGlobal;=0A=
		float att;=0A=
		=0A=
		/* a fragment shader can't write a varying variable, hence we need=0A=
		a new variable to store the normalized interpolated normal */=0A=
		n =3D normalize(normal);=0A=
		=0A=
		/* compute the dot product between normal and normalized lightdir */=0A=
		NdotL =3D max(dot(n,normalize(lightDir)),0.0);=0A=
	=0A=
		if (NdotL &gt; 0.0) {=0A=
		=0A=
			att =3D 1.0 / (gl_LightSource[0].constantAttenuation +=0A=
					gl_LightSource[0].linearAttenuation * dist +=0A=
					gl_LightSource[0].quadraticAttenuation * dist * dist);=0A=
			color +=3D att * (diffuse * NdotL + ambient);=0A=
		=0A=
			=0A=
			halfV =3D normalize(halfVector);=0A=
			NdotHV =3D max(dot(n,halfV),0.0);=0A=
			color +=3D att * gl_FrontMaterial.specular * =
gl_LightSource[0].specular * =0A=
							pow(NdotHV,gl_FrontMaterial.shininess);=0A=
		}=0A=
	=0A=
		gl_FragColor =3D color;=0A=
	}=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>
<P>The following images show the difference between a point light as =
computed by=20
the fixed functionality, i.e. per vertex, and using the shader in this =
tutorial,=20
i.e. per pixel.=20
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE>
  <TBODY>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><IMG width=3D"203" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/pointgl.gif"></TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"205" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/pointpix.gif"></TD></TR>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><I>Fixed Functionality</I></TD>
    <TD><I>Per Pixel</I></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>The full source of the shaders, in a <A=20
href=3D"http://www.typhoonlabs.com/">Shader Designer</A> project can be =
found in=20
<A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/pointlightsd.zip">here</A>.=20
<P>
<H2>Spot Light Per Pixel </H2><BR>This tutorial is based on the previous =

tutorial as most (99%) of the code comes from there. The only thing new =
in a=20
spot light, when compared to a <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#pointlight">point=20
light</A>, is that in the former the light rays are restricted to a cone =
of=20
light where as in the latter the rays are emitted in all directions.=20
<P>From an OpenGL application point of view the differences between the =
two are:=20
<UL>
  <LI>The spot light, besides the position has a direction,=20
  <I>spotDirection</I>, which represents the axis of the cone.</LI>
  <LI>There is an angle of the cone. GLSL offers both the angle, as =
specified in=20
  the application, as well as the cosine which is a derived variable,=20
  <I>spotCosCutoff</I>.</LI>
  <LI>Finally we have a rate of decay, <I>spotExponent</I>, i.e. a =
measure of=20
  how the light intensity decreases from the center to the walls of the=20
  cone.</LI></UL>
<P>The vertex shader is the same as in the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#pointlight">point=20
light</A>. It's in the fragment shader that we're going to make some =
changes.=20
The diffuse, specular and ambient components will only have an effect if =
the=20
fragment being shaded is inside the light's cone. Hence the first thing =
we must=20
do is to check this.=20
<P>The cosine of the angle between the light to vertex vector and the =
spot=20
direction must be larger than <I>spotCosCutofff</I> otherwise the =
fragment is=20
outside the cone and will only receive the global ambient term.=20
<P>
<HR>

<PRE>	...=0A=
	=0A=
	n =3D normalize(normal);=0A=
	=0A=
	/* compute the dot product between normal and ldir */=0A=
	NdotL =3D max(dot(n,normalize(lightDir)),0.0);=0A=
=0A=
	if (NdotL &gt; 0.0) {=0A=
	=0A=
		spotEffect =3D dot(normalize(gl_LightSource[0].spotDirection), =0A=
				normalize(-lightDir));=0A=
		if (spotEffect &gt; gl_LightSource[0].spotCosCutoff) {=0A=
		=0A=
		=0A=
			/* compute the illumination in here */=0A=
		}=0A=
	}=0A=
	=0A=
	gl_FragColor =3D ...=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The computation of the illumination is pretty much the same as in the =
<A=20
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#pointlight">point=20
light</A> case, the only difference being that the attenuation must be=20
multiplied be the spotlight effect using the following equation:=20
<P>
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"429" height=3D"47" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqspoteffect.gif"></CENTER>
<P>where <I>spotDirection</I> is a field from the ligth state (see <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#lights">here</A>),=20
<I>lightDir</I> is the vector from the light source to the vertex, and=20
<I>spotExp</I> is the spot rate of decay. This is also provided by the =
OpenGL=20
state (see <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#lights">here</A>),=20
and controls how the lights intensity decays from the center of the cone =
it its=20
borders. The larger the value the faster de decay, with zero meaning =
constant=20
light within the light cone.=20
<P>
<HR>

<PRE>		spotEffect =3D pow(spotEffect, gl_LightSource[0].spotExponent);=0A=
		att =3D spotEffect / (gl_LightSource[0].constantAttenuation +=0A=
				gl_LightSource[0].linearAttenuation * dist +=0A=
				gl_LightSource[0].quadraticAttenuation * dist * dist);=0A=
			=0A=
		color +=3D att * (diffuse * NdotL + ambient);=0A=
	=0A=
		=0A=
		halfV =3D normalize(halfVector);=0A=
		NdotHV =3D max(dot(n,halfV),0.0);=0A=
		color +=3D att * gl_FrontMaterial.specular * =0A=
				    gl_LightSource[0].specular * =0A=
				    pow(NdotHV,gl_FrontMaterial.shininess);=0A=
=0A=
</PRE>
<HR>

<P>The following images show the difference between a point light as =
computed by=20
the fixed functionality, i.e. per vertex, and using the shader in this =
tutorial,=20
i.e. per pixel.=20
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE>
  <TBODY>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><IMG width=3D"166" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/spotgl.gif"></TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"168" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/spotpix.gif"></TD></TR>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><I>Fixed Functionality</I></TD>
    <TD><I>Per Pixel</I></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>The full source of the shaders, in a <A=20
href=3D"http://www.typhoonlabs.com/">Shader Designer</A> project can be =
found in=20
<A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/spotlightsd.zip">here</A>.=20
<A name=3D"texture"></A>=20
<H2>Simple Texture </H2><BR>In order to perform texturing operations in =
GLSL we=20
need to have access to the texture coordinates per vertex. GLSL provides =
some <A=20
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#oglattribute">attribute</A>=20
variables, one for each texture unit:=20
<PRE>	attribute vec4 gl_MultiTexCoord0;=0A=
	attribute vec4 gl_MultiTexCoord1;=0A=
	attribute vec4 gl_MultiTexCoord2;=0A=
	attribute vec4 gl_MultiTexCoord3;=0A=
	attribute vec4 gl_MultiTexCoord4;=0A=
	attribute vec4 gl_MultiTexCoord5;=0A=
	attribute vec4 gl_MultiTexCoord6;=0A=
	attribute vec4 gl_MultiTexCoord7;=0A=
</PRE>
GLSL also provides access to the texture matrices for each texture unit =
in an <A=20
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#ogluniform">uniform</A>=20
array.=20
<PRE>	uniform mat4 gl_TextureMatrix[gl_MaxTextureCoords];=0A=
</PRE>The vertex=20
shader has access to the attributes defined above to get the texture =
coordinates=20
specified in the OpenGL application. Then it must compute the texture =
coordinate=20
for the vertex and store it in the pre defined varying variable=20
<I>gl_TexCoord[i]</I>, where <I>i</I> indicates the texture unit.=20
<P>The simple following instruction sets the vertex texture coordinate =
for=20
texture unit 0 just by copying the texture coordinate specified in the =
OpenGL=20
application.=20
<PRE>	gl_TexCoord[0]  =3D gl_MultiTexCoord0;=0A=
</PRE>A simple example of a vertex=20
shader to setup texture coordinates for a texture, using texture unit 0, =
could=20
be:=20
<PRE>	void main() {=0A=
	=0A=
		gl_TexCoord[0] =3D gl_MultiTexCoord0;=0A=
		gl_Position =3D ftransform();=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
If we wanted to use the texture matrix then we could write:=20
<PRE>	void main() {=0A=
	=0A=
		gl_TexCoord[0] =3D gl_TextureMatrix[0] * gl_MultiTexCoord0;=0A=
		gl_Position =3D ftransform();=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
As mentioned before <I>gl_TexCoord</I> is a varying variable, i.e. it =
will be=20
used in the fragment shader to access the interpolated texture =
coordinate.=20
<P>In order to access the texture values it is necessary to declare a =
special=20
type of variable in the frament shader. For a 2D texture we could write: =

<PRE>	uniform sampler2D tex;=0A=
</PRE>Data types for 1D and 3D textures are also=20
available, the general format is: sampler<I>i</I>D, where <I>i</I> is =
the=20
dimensionality of the texture. The user defined <I>tex</I> variable =
contains the=20
texture unit we are going to use, in this case 0. The function that =
gives us a=20
texel, a pixel in the texture image, is <I>texture2D</I>. This function =
receives=20
a <I>sampler2D</I>, the texture coordinates, and it returns the texel =
value. The=20
signature is as follows:=20
<PRE>	vec4 texture2D(sampler2D, vec2);=0A=
</PRE>The returned value takes into=20
account all the texture settings as defined in the OpenGL application, =
for=20
instance the filtering, mipmap, clamp, etc... Our fragment shader can =
then be=20
written as:=20
<PRE>	uniform sampler2D tex;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
		vec4 color =3D texture2D(tex,gl_TexCoord[0].st);=0A=
		gl_FragColor =3D color;=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
Notice the usage of selector <I>st</I> when accessing gl_TexCoord. As =
mentioned=20
in section <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#data">Data=20
Types and Variables</A>, when accessing texture coordinates the =
following=20
selectors can be used: s,t,p,q. (Note that <I>r</I> is not used to avoid =

conlficts with rgb selectors).=20
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE>
  <TBODY>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><IMG width=3D"96" height=3D"96" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/crate.jpg"></TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"132" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/texSimple.jpg"></TD></TR>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><I>Texture</I></TD>
    <TD><I>Textured Cube</I></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>A <A href=3D"http://www.typhoonlabs.com/">Shader Designer</A> project =
is=20
available in <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/textureSimple.zip">here</A>.=20
<P>
<H2>Combine Texture + Fragment </H2><BR>OpenGL allows us to combine the =
texture=20
color with the fragments color in several ways. In the next table some =
of the=20
available modes for the RGBA mode are presented:=20
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE cellpadding=3D"5">
  <TBODY>
  <TR>
    <TD align=3D"right">GL_REPLACE</TD>
    <TD align=3D"left">C =3D Ct</TD>
    <TD align=3D"left">A =3D At</TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD align=3D"right">GL_MODULATE</TD>
    <TD align=3D"left">C =3D Ct*Cf</TD>
    <TD align=3D"left">A =3D At*Af</TD></TR>
  <TR>
    <TD align=3D"right">GL_DECAL</TD>
    <TD align=3D"left">C =3D Cf  * (1 - At) + Ct * At</TD>
    <TD align=3D"left">A =3D Af</TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>In the table above <I>Ct</I> and <I>At</I> represent the color and =
alpha=20
value of the texture element, <I>Cf</I> and <I>Af</I> represent the =
color and=20
alpha value of the fragment (prior to applying the texture), and finaly =
<I>C</I>=20
and <I>A</I> represent the final color and alpha.=20
<P>The example provided in the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#texture">previous</A>=20
section is the equivalent of GL_REPLACE. Now we're going to implement =
the=20
equivalent of GL_MODULATE on a lit cube. The shaders will only compute =
the=20
diffuse and ambient component with a white diffuse directional light. =
For the=20
full material definition please see the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#lights">lighting</A>=20
section.=20
<P>Since we're using lights, and therefore normals, the vertex shader =
msut do=20
some extra work. Namely it must transform into eye space and normalize =
the=20
normal, and it must also normalize the light direction (the light =
direction has=20
already been transformed into eye space by OpenGL). The vertex shader is =
now:=20
<PRE>	varying vec3 lightDir,normal;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
	=0A=
		normal =3D normalize(gl_NormalMatrix * gl_Normal);=0A=
		lightDir =3D normalize(vec3(gl_LightSource[0].position));=0A=
		=0A=
		gl_TexCoord[0] =3D gl_MultiTexCoord0;=0A=
		gl_Position =3D ftransform();=0A=
	} =0A=
</PRE>
In the fragment shader the color and alpha of the lit fragment is =
computed into=20
<I>cf</I> and <I>af</I> respectively. The rest of the shader is just =
computing=20
the GL_MODULATE formulas presented above.=20
<PRE>	varying vec3 lightDir,normal;=0A=
	uniform sampler2D tex;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
		vec3 ct,cf;=0A=
		vec4 texel;=0A=
		float intensity,at,af;=0A=
		=0A=
		intensity =3D max(dot(lightDir,normalize(normal)),0.0);=0A=
		=0A=
		cf =3D intensity * (gl_FrontMaterial.diffuse).rgb + =0A=
						  gl_FrontMaterial.ambient.rgb;=0A=
		af =3D gl_FrontMaterial.diffuse.a;=0A=
		=0A=
		texel =3D texture2D(tex,gl_TexCoord[0].st);=0A=
		ct =3D texel.rgb;=0A=
		at =3D texel.a;=0A=
		=0A=
		gl_FragColor =3D vec4(ct * cf, at * af);	=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE>
  <TBODY>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><IMG width=3D"132" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/texSimple.jpg"></TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"126" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/texModulate.jpg"></TD></TR>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><I>GL_REPLACE</I></TD>
    <TD><I>GL_MODULATE</I></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>A <A href=3D"http://www.typhoonlabs.com/">Shader Designer</A> project =
is=20
available in <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/textureComb.zip">here</A>.=20
<P>
<H2>MultiTexture </H2><BR>Multitexturing is also really easy in GLSL. =
All we=20
have to do is to access both textures. And since in here we're going to =
use the=20
same texture coordinates we don't even have to rewrite the vertex =
shader. The=20
fragment shader also suffers a minor change to add both textures colors. =

<PRE>	varying vec3 lightDir,normal;=0A=
	uniform sampler2D tex,l3d;=0A=
	=0A=
	void main()=0A=
	{=0A=
		vec3 ct,cf;=0A=
		vec4 texel;=0A=
		float intensity,at,af;=0A=
		=0A=
		intensity =3D max(dot(lightDir,normalize(normal)),0.0);=0A=
		=0A=
		cf =3D intensity * (gl_FrontMaterial.diffuse).rgb + =0A=
						  gl_FrontMaterial.ambient.rgb;=0A=
		af =3D gl_FrontMaterial.diffuse.a;=0A=
		=0A=
		texel =3D texture2D(tex,gl_TexCoord[0].st)+=0A=
			  texture2D(l3d,gl_TexCoord[0].st);=0A=
		ct =3D texel.rgb;=0A=
		at =3D texel.a;=0A=
		=0A=
		=0A=
		=0A=
		gl_FragColor =3D vec4(ct * cf, at * af);	=0A=
	}=0A=
</PRE>
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE>
  <TBODY>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><IMG width=3D"96" height=3D"96" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/crate.jpg"></TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"96" height=3D"96" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/l3d.jpg"></TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"156" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/texMulti.jpg"></TD></TR>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><I>Texture Unit 0</I></TD>
    <TD><I>Texture Unit 1</I></TD>
    <TD><I>Textured Cube</I></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>And now for something a little different: a glow in the dark effect. =
We want=20
the second texture to glow in the dark, i.e. it will be fully bright =
when the=20
light doesn't hit, and it will be dimmed as it gets more light.=20
<P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE>
  <TBODY>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><IMG width=3D"156" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/texMulti.jpg"></TD>
    <TD><IMG width=3D"147" height=3D"128" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/texGlow.jpg"></TD></TR>
  <TR align=3D"center">
    <TD><I>Additive Multi-Texture</I></TD>
    <TD><I>Glowing =
Multi-Texture</I></TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></CENTER>We have to=20
recompute the final color in two steps: first we compute a color which =
is the=20
first texture modulated with the fragments color, and afterwards we add =
the=20
second texture unit depending on the intensity.=20
<P>If <I>intensity</I> is zero then we want the second texture in its =
full=20
strength. When the <I>intensity</I> is 1 we only want a 10% contribution =
of the=20
second texture unit. For all the other values of <I>intensity</I> we =
want to=20
interpolate. We can achieve this with the <I>smoothstep</I> function. =
This=20
function has the following signature:=20
<PRE>	genType smoothStep(genType edge0, genType edge1, genType x);=0A=
</PRE>The=20
result will be zero if <I>x</I> &lt;=3D <I>edge0</I>, 1 if <I>x</I> =
&gt;=3D=20
<I>edge1</I> and performs smooth Hermite interpolation between 0 and 1 =
when=20
<I>edge0 </I>&lt; <I>x</I> &lt; <I>edge1</I>. In our case we want to =
call the=20
function as follows:=20
<PRE>	coef =3D smoothStep(1.0, 0.2, intensity);=0A=
</PRE>The following fragment=20
shader does the trick:=20
<PRE>varying vec3 lightDir,normal;=0A=
uniform sampler2D tex,l3d;=0A=
=0A=
void main()=0A=
{=0A=
	vec3 ct,cf,c;=0A=
	vec4 texel;=0A=
	float intensity,at,af,a;=0A=
	=0A=
	intensity =3D max(dot(lightDir,normalize(normal)),0.0);=0A=
	=0A=
	cf =3D intensity * (gl_FrontMaterial.diffuse).rgb + =0A=
					  gl_FrontMaterial.ambient.rgb;=0A=
	af =3D gl_FrontMaterial.diffuse.a;=0A=
	=0A=
	texel =3D texture2D(tex,gl_TexCoord[0].st);=0A=
		=0A=
	ct =3D texel.rgb;=0A=
	at =3D texel.a;=0A=
	=0A=
	c =3D cf * ct;=0A=
	a =3D af * at;=0A=
		=0A=
	float coef =3D smoothstep(1.0,0.2,intensity);=0A=
	c +=3D coef *  vec3(texture2D(l3d,gl_TexCoord[0].st));=0A=
	=0A=
	gl_FragColor =3D vec4(c, a);	=0A=
}=0A=
</PRE>
A <A href=3D"http://www.typhoonlabs.com/">Shader Designer</A> project is =
available=20
in <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/examples/textureGlow.zip">here</A>.=20
<P><A name=3D"normalmatrix"></A>=20
<H2>The gl_NormalMatrix </H2><BR>The gl_NormalMatrix is present in many =
vertex=20
shaders. In here some light is shed on what is this matrix and what is =
it for.=20
This section was inspired by the excellent book by Eric Lengyel =
"Mathematics for=20
3D Game Programming and Computer Graphics".=20
<P>Many computations are done in eye space. This has to do with the fact =
that=20
lighting needs to be performed in this space, otherwise eye position =
dependent=20
effects, such as specular lights would be harder to implement.=20
<P>Hence we need a way to transform the normal into eye space. To =
transform a=20
vertex to eye space we can write:=20
<P>
<PRE>	vertexEyeSpace =3D gl_ModelViewMatrix * gl_Vertex;=0A=
</PRE>
<P>So why can't we just do the same with a normal vector? First a normal =
is a=20
vector of 3 floats and the modelview matrix is 4x4. This could be easily =

overcome with the following code:=20
<P>
<PRE>	normalEyeSpace =3D vec3(gl_ModelViewMatrix * vec4(gl_Normal,0.0));=0A=
</PRE>
<P>So, <I>gl_NormalMatrix</I> is just a shortcut to simplify code =
writing? No,=20
not really. The above line of code will work in some circunstances but =
not all.=20
<P>Lets have a look at a potential problem:=20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"168" height=3D"138" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/normalmat1.gif">=20
</CENTER>In the above figure we see a triangle, with a normal and a =
tangent=20
vectors. The following figure shows what happens when the modelview =
matrix=20
contains a non-uniform scale. =20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"160" height=3D"181" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/normalmat2.gif">=20
</CENTER>Note: if the scale was uniform, then the direction of the =
normal would=20
have been preserved, The length would have been affected but this can be =
easily=20
fixed with a normalization.=20
<P>In the above figure the modelview matrix was applied to all the =
vertices as=20
well as to the normal and the result is clearly wrong: the normal is no =
longer=20
perpendicular to the surface. =20
<P>So now we know that we can't apply the modelview in all cases to =
transform=20
the normal vector. The question is then, what matrix should we apply?=20
<P>We know that, prior to the matrix transformation T.N =3D 0, since the =
vectors=20
are by definition perpendicular. We also know that after the =
transformation=20
N'.T' must remain equal to zero, since they must remain perpendicular to =
each=20
other. Let's assume that the matrix G is the correct matrix to transform =
the=20
normal vector. T can be multiplied safely by the upper left 3x3 =
submatrix of the=20
modelview (T is a vector, hence the w component is zero). This is =
because T can=20
be computed as the difference between two vertices, therefore the same =
matrix=20
that is used to transform the vertices can be used to transform T. Hence =
the=20
following equation:=20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"238" height=3D"32" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqnm1.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>The dot product can be transformed into a product of vectors, =
therefore: =20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"288" height=3D"35" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqnm2.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>Note that the transpose of the first vector must be considered since =
this is=20
required to multiply the vectors. We also know that the transpose of a=20
multiplication is the multiplication of the transposes, hence:=20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"252" height=3D"33" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqnm3.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>We started by stating that the dot product between N and T was zero, =
so if=20
the following equation is true then we are on the right track.=20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"105" height=3D"38" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqnm4.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>Applying a little algebra yieds=20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"126" height=3D"32" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqnm5.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>Therefore the correct matrix to transform the normal is the transpose =
of the=20
inverse of the M matrix. OpenGL computes this for us in the=20
<I>gl_NormalMatrix</I>. =20
<P>In the beginning of this section it was stated that using the =
modelview=20
matrix would work in some cases. Whenever the 3x3 upper left submatrix =
of the=20
modelview is orthogonal we have:=20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"219" height=3D"34" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/eqnm6.gif">=20
</CENTER>
<P>This is because with an orthogonal matrix, the transpose is the same =
as the=20
inverse. So what is an orthogonal matrix? An orthogonal matrix is a =
matrix where=20
all columns/rows are unit length, and are mutually perpendicular. This =
implies=20
that when two vectors are multiplied by such a matrix, the angle between =
them=20
after transformation by an orthogonal matrix is the same as prior to =
that=20
transformation. Simply put the transformation preserves the angle =
relation=20
between vectors, hence normals remain perpendicular to tangents! =
Furthermore it=20
preserves the length of the vectors as well.=20
<P>So when can we be sure that M is orthogonal? When we limit our =
geometric=20
operations to rotations and translations, i.e. when in the OpenGL =
application we=20
only use <I>glRotate</I> and gl_Translate and not <I>glScale</I>. These=20
operations guarantee that M is orthogonal. Note: <I>gluLookAt</I> also =
creates=20
an orthogonal matrix!=20
<P>
<P><A name=3D"normalization"></A>=20
<H2>Normalization Issues </H2><BR><B>Vertex Shader</B>=20
<P>The dot product is commonly used to compute the cosine of the angle =
between=20
two vectors. As we know this will only hold if both vectors are =
normalized. This=20
is why we use the normalization operation in many shaders. In here we =
will see=20
when we can skip this step, and we must use it.=20
<P>When a normal vector arrives at a vertex shader is common to =
normalize it=20
<P>
<PRE>	normal =3D normalize(gl_NormalMatrix * gl_Normal);=0A=
</PRE>
<P>The multiplication by the <A =
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#normalmatrix">gl_NormaMatrix</A>=20
transforms the incoming normal to eye-space. The normalization =
guarantees a unit=20
length vector as required to compute the cosine with a dot product.=20
<P>So can we avoid the normalization? We'll in some cases we can. If the =
<A=20
href=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutoria=
l/index.html#normalmatrix">gl_NormaMatrix</A>=20
is orthogonal then we know that the length of the incoming vector is =
preserved,=20
i.e. the length of <I>normal</I> is equal to the length of =
<I>gl_Normal</I>.=20
Therefore, if the normals from the OpenGL application are normalized, =
which is=20
common, we can avoid the normalization in the shader.=20
<P>In practice this means that if we use <I>gluLookAt</I> to set the =
camera, and=20
then perform only rotations and translations on our models, we can skip =
the=20
normalization of the normal vector in the shader. It also means that a=20
directional light will have its direction already normalized.=20
<P>
<P><B>Fragment Shader</B>
<P>In the fragment shader we often find ourselves normalizing a vector =
which was=20
just normalized in the vertex shader. Do we really need to do this? =
Well, the=20
answer is yes, in most cases we do.=20
<P>Consider a triangle with three different per vertex normal vectors. =
The=20
fragment shader receives an interpolated normal, based on the distance =
from the=20
fragment to the three vertices. The problem is that the interpolated =
vector,=20
although it has the right direction, it doesn't have unit length.=20
<P>The following diagram shows why this is the case. The black lines =
represent=20
the faces (in 2D), the normals at the vertices are represented in blue. =
The=20
green vector represents an interpolated normal at the fragment =
(represented with=20
a dot). All interpolated normals will lie the dotted line. As can be =
seen in the=20
figure, the green vector is smaller than the blue vectors (which are =
unit=20
length, at least that was my intention :) ).=20
<CENTER><IMG width=3D"284" height=3D"205" =
src=3D"http://zach.in.tu-clausthal.de/teaching/cg_literatur/glsl_tutorial=
/images/normalinter.gif">=20
</CENTER>Note that if the vertex normals were not normalized, not only =
the=20
length would be different from one, but also the direction would be =
worng in the=20
general case. Hence, even if a vector isn't used on a vertex shader, if =
we need=20
to have it normalized in the fragment shader, we must also normalize it =
on the=20
vertex shader.=20
<P>There is however a case when normalization can be skipped in the =
fragment=20
shader, as long as the vectors per vertex are normalized. This is when =
the=20
vectors per vertex all share the same direction, i.e. they are equal. =
The=20
interpolation of such vectors would yield exactly the same vertex as the =
per=20
vertex vectors, hence normalized (we assumed that the vertex vectors =
were=20
normlized).=20
<P>A simple example is when one considers a directional light. The =
direction is=20
constant for all fragments, so if the direction is previously =
normalized, we can=20
skip the normalization step in the fragment shader.
<P></P></BODY></HTML>

